{"title_page": "K-1", "text_new": "{{other uses|K1 (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = K-1 Global Holdings Limited\n| logo = [[File:K-1 Logo.png]]\n| vector_logo =\n| type = Private\n| genre =\n| foundation = 1993\n| location_city = [[Hong Kong]]\n| location_country =\n| founders = [[Kazuyoshi Ishii]]\n| key_people = Amanda Yang,  Director Management & Administration\nAlin H\u0103lm\u0103gean, Director Operations<br />\nNed Kuruc, Director Operations\n| area_served =\n| industry = Martial-arts entertainment planning and promotion\n| products =\n| revenue =\n| operating_income =\n| net_income =\n| num_employees =\n| divisions =\n| subsid =\n| owner = K-1 Global Holdings Limited\n| homepage = [http://www.k-1world.com/ K-1 Global]<br/>[https://www.k-1.co.jp/ K-1 Japan]\n| dissolved =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n'''K-1''' is a [[martial arts]] organisation and martial arts brand established in 1993, well-known worldwide mainly for its heavyweight division fights.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=qtsDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT45&dq=k-1&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiazZ7A-4bLAhXB0hoKHatGDaM4ChDoAQhIMAk#v=onepage&q=k-1&f=false |title=Black Belt |website=Books.google.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2016-02-20}}</ref> In January 2012, K-1 Global Holdings Limited, a company registered in Hong Kong, acquired the rights to K-1, and is the current organizer of K-1 events worldwide.\n\n== Name ==\nThe letter [[K]] in K-1 is officially designated as a representation of words [[karate]], [[kickboxing]] and [[kung fu]]. Nevertheless, some reports suggest that it represents the initial K found in competing disciplines such as karate, kickboxing, kung fu, [[kempo]], ''kakutougi'' (the generic Japanese term for \"combat sports\"), and [[taekwondo|[tae] kwon do]].<ref name=\"TashiroTyrangiel2001\">Tashiro, H., & Tyrangiel, J. (2001): [http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1000699,00.html Turning the martial arts into mondo mayhem] ''TIME'' (September 3, 2001). Retrieved on March 4, 2010.</ref> Yet another theory claims that the K simply comes from ''kakutougi'' and the \"1\" component pertains to the single weight division (in earlier competition) and the champion's unique position.<ref name=\"Maylam2001\">Maylam, J. (2001): [http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/fl20011021a1.html K-1 hits the spot: Ultimate fighters pack a punch] ''The Japan Times'' (October 21, 2001). Retrieved on March 4, 2010.</ref> Nevertheless, the promotion held several tournaments under K-2 and K-3 banners from 1993 to 1995.\n\n==History==\n{{Main|History of K-1}}\nK-1's predecessor [[Seidokaikan]] Karate was formed in 1980 by [[Kazuyoshi Ishii]], a former Kyokushin karate practitioner who had formed his own organization to help promote the best stand-up martial artists.<ref name=\"fightmagazine\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fightmagazine.com/mma-magazine/k-1-502/|title=K-1 &#124; &nbsp;FIGHT! Magazine &#8211; Archives|publisher=fightmagazine.com|accessdate=2014-04-06}}</ref> Seidokaikan arranged several successful challenge events against other martial arts organizations, originally using rules based on the Kyokushin Knockdown karate rules, but gradually adapting and changing closer to kickboxing rules. In 1993, Mr. Ishii founded the K-1 organization exclusively as a kickboxing organization, closely cooperating with, but independent from Seidokaikan.<ref name=\"Maylam2001\"/>\n\n===Financial problems===\nStarting in 2010, multiple stories began to surface regarding the financial troubles of K-1 and their parent company FEG.<ref>[http://sportsnavi.yahoo.co.jp/fight/headlines/20110121-00000014-spnavi-fight.html \"The Showtime May Arena event would possibly be delayed, due to K-1's financial problems\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110124192156/http://sportsnavi.yahoo.co.jp/fight/headlines/20110121-00000014-spnavi-fight.html |date=2011-01-24 }}, January 21, 2011, ''[[Yahoo!|Sports Navi \u2013 Yahoo! Japan]]'' {{in lang|ja}}</ref> Simon Rutz, the owner of the [[Netherlands|Dutch]]-based kickboxing promotion [[It's Showtime (kickboxing)|It's Showtime]], claimed in January 2011 that some fighters from It's Showtime had not been paid for fights in K-1.<ref>[http://sportsnavi.yahoo.co.jp/fight/k1/text/201101260006-spnavi_1.html \"What is happening with K-1!? It's Showtime owner Rutz talks about the rumor (1/2)\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120930103229/http://sportsnavi.yahoo.co.jp/fight/k1/text/201101260006-spnavi_1.html |date=2012-09-30 }}, January 21, 2011, ''[[Yahoo!|Sports Navi \u2013 Yahoo! Japan]]'' {{in lang|ja}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2011, [[Fighting and Entertainment Group|FEG]] publicly announced that they were facing financial problems and that the organization would take some months off to restructure. Many fighters and managers spoke out against FEG due to unpaid fight purses and objections to the direction that its owner was taking K-1. It appeared that financial problems were severe, and that FEG could potentially lose ownership of K-1.<ref>[http://news.livedoor.com/article/detail/5289165/ \"K-1 could be purchased after a financial problem!? Like Pride?\"], January 23, 2011, ''[[Livedoor|Livedoor Sports]]'' {{in lang|ja}}</ref>\n\nThe entire K-1 brand, along with most of its trademarks, with the exception of, 'K-1 Koshien', 'K-1 MAX' and '[[Dream (mixed martial arts)|Dream]]', were sold to  Japanese real estate firm, Barbizon Corporation Limited, on July 28, 2011.<ref>[http://www.mmafighting.com/2011/07/28/k-1-sold-to-japanese-real-estate-firm-barbizon/ \"K-1 Sold to Japanese Real Estate Firm Barbizon\"], July 28, 2011, ''[[Aol|MMAFighting]]''</ref>\n\nOn February 1, 2012 EMCOM Entertainment Inc. purchased K-1 from Barbizon.<ref>[http://liverkick.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1258:qmr-kimq-acquires-k-1&catid=36:k-1 K-1 announces agreement with SuperKombat], February 1, 2012, Liver Kick</ref>\n\n===K-1 Global===\nIn March 2012, It's Showtime announced that EMCOM Entertainment established a new company K-1 Global Holdings Ltd. in [[Hong Kong]]. K-1 Global Holdings, Ltd., became the new official owner of the K-1 brand. K-1 Global's agreement with promotion required that certain fighters signed under It's Showtime appear in upcoming K-1 Global events.<ref>[http://www.itsshowtime.nl/index.php?p=news&id=1497 It's Showtime Closes Deal with the New K-1 Organization], March 6, 2012, It's Showtime</ref>\n\nA number of events were already planned and scheduled for the 2012 calendar before new K-1 ownership took complete control of the company. It's Showtime was the promoter of the first event presented by K-1 Global Holdings Ltd., the [[K-1 World MAX 2012 World Championship Tournament Final 16#K-1 World MAX 2012 World Championship Tournament Final 16|K-1 World MAX Final 16]]. It took place on May 27, 2012 at the Palacio Vistalegre in Madrid, Spain.\n\nAfter the event, controversy and rumors circulated over the fact that once again, fighters were not paid for their performances. Problems were compounded due to unpaid financial obligations of FEG, and the complete transfer of ownership of the K-1 name was not yet complete. As a result, the K-1 World Grand Prix scheduled for 2012 would be cancelled if these issues were not resolved.<ref>[http://www.mmafighting.com/2011/10/17/simon-rutz-k-1-world-grand-prix-cancelled-feg-technically-bank Simon Rutz: \"K-1 World Grand Prix Canceled, FEG 'Technically Bankrupt\"], October 17, 2011, Mmafighting.com</ref>\n\nUltimately, K-1 Global Holdings, Ltd. was blamed for the failure of an event they did not promote. They were also accused of not paying fighters when in fact, the promoter and FEG shared responsibilities in ensuring fighters were paid. The Chairman of the new K-1 resolved the matter by paying fighters what was owed and including a 50% bonus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://liverkick.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1260:daniel-ghita-gives-us-insight-into-k-1s-future-and-a-fragmented-kickboxing-world&catid=36:k-1|title=Daniel Ghita gives us insight into K-1's future and a fragmented kickboxing world|publisher=Liverkick.com|accessdate=2015-10-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107065544/http://liverkick.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1260:daniel-ghita-gives-us-insight-into-k-1s-future-and-a-fragmented-kickboxing-world&catid=36:k-1|archive-date=2016-01-07|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIt was announced in June 2012 that It's Showtime was purchased by Glory Sports International, eventually to be merged in their new promotion [[Glory (kickboxing)|GLORY]].<ref>[http://www.gloryworldseries.com/en/news%2F28-glory-world-series-acquires-kickboxing-competitor-it-s-showtime ]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120906055541/http://www.gloryworldseries.com/en/news/28-glory-world-series-acquires-kickboxing-competitor-it-s-showtime |date=September 6, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nOn August 10, 2012 K-1's co-promotion agreement with [[Romania]]n-based kickboxing promotion SUPERKOMBAT was announced.<ref>[http://liverkick.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1774:k-1-announces-agreement-with-superkombat&catid=36:k-1 K-1 announces agreement with SuperKombat], August 10, 2012, Liverkick.com</ref> Eventually it was ended. Early 2013 SK president [[Eduard Irimia]] stated that its company will be independent in 2013 but will still continue to have cooperation with any interested promotion including K-1 by offering fighters.<ref>[http://liverkick.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2310:liverkicks-exclusive-interview-with-superkombat-president-eduard-irimia-pt-1&catid=43:interviews Liverkick's Exclusive Interview with Superkombat President Eduard Irimia], February 19, 2013, Liverkick.com</ref>\n\n===List of K-1 events===\n{{Main|List of K-1 events}}\n{{See also|List of Hero's events}}\n\nIn the past every year there were dozens of other K-1 qualifying tournaments and preliminaries held around the world.\n\nK-1 has held events in many countries around the world.\n\nThe following is a list of countries that K-1 has held events in chronological order:\n*{{flagicon|JPN}} [[Japan]] (1993\u20132012, 2014-2018)\n*{{flagicon|NED}} [[Netherlands]] (1994, 2001\u20132003, 2006\u20132010)\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} [[France]] (1995, 2002\u20132008, 2010)\n*{{flagicon|SWI}} [[Switzerland]] (1995\u20132000, 2003, 2017)\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[United States]] (1998, 2000\u20132008, 2012)\n*{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Australia]] (2000\u20132005, 2010)\n*{{flagicon|ENG}} [[England]] (2000, 2002\u20132004, 2006\u20132007, 2013)\n*{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Italy]] (2000\u20132008)\n*{{flagicon|GER}} [[Germany]] (2000\u20132008)\n*{{flagicon|Belarus}} [[Belarus]] (2000, 2010)\n*{{flagicon|CRO}} [[Croatia]] (2000, 2002, 2007, 2009\u20132010, 2013)\n*{{flagicon|RSA}} [[South Africa]] (2000\u20132002, 2006)\n*{{flagicon|NZ}} New Zealand (2000\u20132006)\n*{{flagicon|Czech Republic}} [[Czech Republic]] (2000\u20132001, 2006\u20132009)\n*{{flagicon|DEN}} [[Denmark]] (2001)\n*{{flagicon|UKR}} [[Ukraine]] (2001\u20132002, 2006, 2010)\n*{{flagicon|ESP}} [[Spain]] (2002\u20132004, 2005\u20132006, 2012\u20132014)\n*{{flagicon|BRA}} [[Brazil]] (2002\u20132006, 2013)\n*{{flagicon|SWE}} [[Sweden]] (2003\u20132010)\n*{{flagicon|RUS}} [[Russia]] (2003, 2006, 2010)\n*{{flagicon|Bosnia}} [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] (2003\u20132004, 2009, 2016)\n*{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Scotland]] (2004)\n*{{flagicon|POR}} [[Portugal]] (2004, 2006, 2013)\n*{{flagicon|POL}} [[Poland]] (2004, 2007\u20132010)\n*{{flagicon|South Korea}} [[South Korea]] (2004\u20132010, 2013)\n*{{flagicon|SLO}} [[Slovenia]] (2005\u20132006, 2008)\n*{{flagicon|HUN}} [[Hungary]] (2005\u20132010)\n*{{flagicon|LIT}} [[Lithuania]] (2006\u20132007, 2010, 2013)\n*{{flagicon|LAT}} [[Latvia]] (2006\u20132008)\n*{{flagicon|TUR}} [[Turkey]] (2007, 2010)\n*{{flagicon|BEL}} [[Belgium]] (2007)\n*{{flagicon|EST}} [[Estonia]] (2007, 2009)\n*{{flagicon|ROM}} [[Romania]] (2007, 2009\u20132010)\n*{{flagicon|Hong Kong}} [[Hong Kong]] (2007)\n*{{flagicon|Austria}} [[Austria]] (2008)\n*{{flagicon|TAI}} [[Taiwan]] (2008)\n*{{flagicon|Moldova}} [[Moldova]] (2009\u20132010, 2013)\n*{{flagicon|China}} [[China]] (2013-2015)\n*{{flagicon|Greece}} [[Greece]] (2012)\n*{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Canada]] (2013)\n*{{flagicon|IRE}} [[Ireland]] (2013)\n*{{flagicon|AZE}} [[Azerbaijan]] (2014)\n*{{flagicon|THA}} [[Thailand]] (2014)\n*{{flagicon|Serbia}} [[Serbia]] (2016)\n\n==Tournament format==\n[[File:K-1 system 2009.jpg|thumb|305px|right|K-1 Qualifying System 2009]]\n\n===K-1 Grand Prix===\n{{Main|K-1 World Grand Prix}}\n\nOriginal K-1 Grand Prix was a single event tournament held in Japan where competitors participated on invitation. By 1998, K-1 introduced the [[K-1 World Grand Prix]] format composed of  K-1 Regional Elimination Tournaments (theoretically amounting to six), which qualify fighters for the K-1 World Grand Prix Final, along with licensed K-1 Fighting Network events designed to hold national preliminaries for regional qualification. However, given the fact that K-1's popularity differs greatly among six K-1 regions, which may limit the number of actual elimination tournaments or change locations. For example, K-1 attempted to gain popularity in the United States by holding two GPs, however only a few Americans have ever qualified for the Finals. In 2006 one of the American GPs was relocated to [[Auckland]]. Additionally the K-1 [[Paris, France|Paris]] GP lost its qualifying right in favor of [[Amsterdam, Netherlands|Amsterdam]]. Eventually Amsterdam lost it in favor of [[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a, Poland|\u0141\u00f3d\u017a]], and then \u0141\u00f3d\u017a in favor of [[Bucharest, Romania|Bucharest]].\n\nK-1 World Grand Prix Final Eliminator (\"Final 16\") is an event where 16 participants compete for the final eight spots in the Final (\"Final 8\"). Eight participants from the Final Eliminator meet at the K-1 World Grand Prix Final. Lesser elements in the tournament format have been significantly modified in years. The final was held at [[Tokyo Dome]] from 1997 to 2006. The 2012 final took place for the first time in history outside Japan, in [[Zagreb, Croatia]].\n\n===K-1 World MAX and other===\nBy 2002, K-1 started the K-1 World MAX (\"Middleweight Artistic Xtreme\") tournament for 70&nbsp;kg (154&nbsp;lb) Middleweight division, following a similar scheme to K-1 World Grand Prix (with theoretically four regional eliminators). In 2007, K-1 introduced two new title belts separate from K-1 World GP Champions, Super Heavyweight World Title for fighters over 100&nbsp;kg/220&nbsp;lbs and Heavyweight World Title for fighters under 100&nbsp;kg/156\u2013220&nbsp;lbs.\n\n==Rules==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=December 2012}}\n*Each match is three or five rounds in duration, with each round lasting three minutes.\n*The match can end by Knockout, Technical Knockout, Decision, Disqualification, Draw or No Contest.\n*Both the referee and the ring doctor have full authority to stop the fight.\n*The fight is scored by three judges on a ten-point must system (The winner of each round receives ten points, and the loser receives nine or less. If the round is even, both competitors receive ten points).\n*If there is a draw after three rounds, the judges' scores are thrown out and one or two extra three-minute rounds are contested. The judges' decision will then come from the scoring of each extra round only. If, after the extra round(s), there is still a draw, the judges will decide a winner based on the flow of the entire match, considering even the slightest difference. A fight can only end in a draw if both fighters go down at the same time and cannot get up, or in the case of accidental injury in the late stages of the contest.\n*Three knockdowns in a round ends the contest, declared a [[technical knockout]].\n*The mandatory eight count is in effect (regardless when the fallen fighter rises, the referee must count to at least \"eight\" on all knockdowns).\n*The standing eight count is in effect (the referee has the right to declare a knockdown on a fighter who appears to be in a dangerous condition to continue in the match).\n*A fighter can be saved by the bell only in the last round.\n\nIn K-1 single elimination tournament matches:\n*Each match is three rounds in duration.\n*Except in the final, two knockdowns in a round ends the contest, declared a [[technical knockout]].\n*One or two reserve fights are held prior to the single elimination matches. If for any reason a fighter who wins and advances through the brackets is unable to continue, a reserve match competitor, or the fighter's opponent from the most recent match, takes his place. There are certain exceptions to this rule (i.e. a fighter who lost a match by knockout might not be eligible to replace another fighter).\n\n===Fouls===\nThe following actions in K-1 are considered fouls:<ref>[http://www.k-1.co.jp/en/what/rules.html]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100809143241/http://www.k-1.co.jp/en/what/rules.html |date=August 9, 2010 }}</ref>\n*Using the head or elbow to deliver a blow\n*Attacking the opponent in the groin\n*Delivering wrestling or judo throwing or submission techniques\n*Thumbing, choking or biting the opponent\n*Punching the opponent in the throat\n*Attacking the opponent while he is down or in the process of getting up\n*Attacking the opponent after the referee calls a break\n*Holding the ropes\n*Using offensive language to the referee\n*Attacking the back of the head with a punch\n*Attempting to cause the opponent to fall out of the ring\n*Voluntarily exiting the ring during the course of a match\n*Attacking an opponent who turns around and shows his back (if the opponent loses his will to fight)\n*Delivering a backspin blow in an unauthorized area\n*Charging inside the opponent's arms with the head held low (inducing a head-butt)\n*Fighting in a passive manner (without attacking), including continuous holding and clinching\n*Attacking more than once while holding the opponent's kicking leg, or while holding the opponent's neck with both hands\n\nA fighter is penalized as follows:\n*Caution&nbsp;\u2013 verbal reprimand by the referee\n*Warning&nbsp;\u2013 fighter is shown a yellow card\n*Point Deduction&nbsp;\u2013 fighter is shown a red card\n\nTwo cautions result in one warning. Two warnings result in a point deduction, and three point deductions in one round can result in a disqualification.\n\nA red card is shown automatically if a fighter commits a foul with malicious intent.\n\n==Popularity/Media==\nKickboxing is very popular in [[Japan]], [[South Korea]], [[Brazil]], and in [[Europe]] in countries such as the [[Netherlands]], [[Croatia]] and [[Romania]] but recently enjoys only limited popularity in the [[United States]].\n\nIn the past the events were frequently shown on [[Tokyo Broadcasting System]] and [[Fuji Television|Fuji TV]]<ref name=\"headkicklegend\">{{cite web|url=http://www.headkicklegend.com/2010/3/31/1398385/k-1-world-grand-prix-yokohama-to|title=Bad Left Hook, Global Boxing News and Commentary|publisher=Headkicklegend.com|accessdate=2014-04-06}}</ref> in Japan, XTM in South Korea, Combate and [[SporTV]] in Brazil, [[HDNet Fights]]<ref>[http://www.sherdog.com/news/press%20releases/k-1-to-air-on-hdnet-15257 ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091029042332/http://www.sherdog.com/news/press%20releases/k-1-to-air-on-hdnet-15257 |date=October 29, 2009 }}</ref> in the United States and on [[Eurosport]] in Europe.\n\nAfter the 'Katougi boom', and the loss of a mainstream network deal, [[AbemaTV]] became K-1's primary broadcaster.<ref>https://abema.tv/timetable</ref> K-1 Japan Group also operates a YouTube channel where fights, press conferences, and general media is uploaded.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/user/k1WorldLeague</ref>\n\n==List of K-1 champions==\n{{main|List of K-1 champions}}\n\n===Current champions===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Division!!Champion!!Since!!Title defences\n|-\n| [[Super Heavyweight]]  || {{flagicon|NED}} [[Roel Mannaart]]  || 2018 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1\n|-\n| [[Cruiserweight (MMA)|Cruiserweight]] (-90&nbsp;kg) ||{{flagicon|Iran}} [[Sina Karimian]]|| 2019 ||style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2\n|-\n| [[Super Welterweight]] (-70&nbsp;kg) || {{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Minoru Kimura]] || 2020 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 0\n|-\n| [[Welterweight]] (-67.5&nbsp;kg) || {{flagicon|JPN}} [[Yuta Kubo]] || 2017 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 3\n|-\n| [[Super Lightweight]] (-65&nbsp;kg) || {{flagicon|JPN}} [[Rukiya Anpo]] || 2019 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2\n|-\n| [[Lightweight]] (-62.5&nbsp;kg) || {{flagicon|JPN}} [[Kenta Hayashi]] || 2019 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 0\n|-\n| [[Super Featherweight]] (-60&nbsp;kg) || {{flagicon|JPN}} [[Takeru Segawa]] || 2017 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1\n|-\n| [[Featherweight]] (-57.5&nbsp;kg) || {{flagicon|JPN}} [[Yuki Egawa]] || 2019 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 0\n|-\n| [[Super Bantamweight]] (-55&nbsp;kg) || {{flagicon|JPN}} [[Yoshiki Takei]] || 2017 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Martial arts}}\n*[[List of K-1 events]]\n*[[List of K-1 champions]]\n*[[List of male kickboxers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.k-1world.com/}}\n*[https://www.k-1.co.jp/ K-1 Japan]\n\n{{Kickboxing organizations}}\n{{Martial arts}}\n\n[[Category:K-1| ]]\n[[Category:Kickboxing organizations]]\n[[Category:Sports organizations established in 1993]]\n[[Category:1993 establishments in Japan]]\n[[Category:Kickboxing in Japan]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses|K1 (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = K-1 Global Holdings Limited\n| logo = [[File:K-1 Logo.png]]\n| vector_logo =\n| type = Private\n| genre =\n| foundation = 1993\n| location_city = [[Hong Kong]]\n| location_country =\n| founders = [[Kazuyoshi Ishii]]\n| key_people = Amanda Yang,  Director Management & Administration\nAlin H\u0103lm\u0103gean, Director Operations<br />\nNed Kuruc, Director Operations\n| area_served =\n| industry = Martial-arts entertainment planning and promotion\n| products =\n| revenue =\n| operating_income =\n| net_income =\n| num_employees =\n| divisions =\n| subsid =\n| owner = K-1 Global Holdings Limited\n| homepage = [http://www.k-1world.com/ K-1 Global]<br/>[https://www.k-1.co.jp/ K-1 Japan]\n| dissolved =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n'''K-1''' is a [[martial arts]] organisation and martial arts brand established in 1993, well-known worldwide mainly for its heavyweight division fights.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=qtsDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT45&dq=k-1&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiazZ7A-4bLAhXB0hoKHatGDaM4ChDoAQhIMAk#v=onepage&q=k-1&f=false |title=Black Belt |website=Books.google.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2016-02-20}}</ref> In January 2012, K-1 Global Holdings Limited, a company registered in Hong Kong, acquired the rights to K-1, and is the current organizer of K-1 events worldwide.\n\n== Name ==\nThe letter [[K]] in K-1 is officially designated as a representation of words [[karate]], [[kickboxing]] and [[kung fu]]. Nevertheless, some reports suggest that it represents the initial K found in competing disciplines such as karate, kickboxing, kung fu, [[kempo]], ''kakutougi'' (the generic Japanese term for \"combat sports\"), and [[taekwondo|[tae] kwon do]].<ref name=\"TashiroTyrangiel2001\">Tashiro, H., & Tyrangiel, J. (2001): [http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1000699,00.html Turning the martial arts into mondo mayhem] ''TIME'' (September 3, 2001). Retrieved on March 4, 2010.</ref> Yet another theory claims that the K simply comes from ''kakutougi'' and the \"1\" component pertains to the single weight division (in earlier competition) and the champion's unique position.<ref name=\"Maylam2001\">Maylam, J. (2001): [http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/fl20011021a1.html K-1 hits the spot: Ultimate fighters pack a punch] ''The Japan Times'' (October 21, 2001). Retrieved on March 4, 2010.</ref> Nevertheless, the promotion held several tournaments under K-2 and K-3 banners from 1993 to 1995.\n\n==History==\n{{Main|History of K-1}}\nK-1's predecessor [[Seidokaikan]] Karate was formed in 1980 by [[Kazuyoshi Ishii]], a former Kyokushin karate practitioner who had formed his own organization to help promote the best stand-up martial artists.<ref name=\"fightmagazine\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fightmagazine.com/mma-magazine/k-1-502/|title=K-1 &#124; &nbsp;FIGHT! Magazine &#8211; Archives|publisher=fightmagazine.com|accessdate=2014-04-06}}</ref> Seidokaikan arranged several successful challenge events against other martial arts organizations, originally using rules based on the Kyokushin Knockdown karate rules, but gradually adapting and changing closer to kickboxing rules. In 1993, Mr. Ishii founded the K-1 organization exclusively as a kickboxing organization, closely cooperating with, but independent from Seidokaikan.<ref name=\"Maylam2001\"/>\n\n===Financial problems===\nStarting in 2010, multiple stories began to surface regarding the financial troubles of K-1 and their parent company FEG.<ref>[http://sportsnavi.yahoo.co.jp/fight/headlines/20110121-00000014-spnavi-fight.html \"The Showtime May Arena event would possibly be delayed, due to K-1's financial problems\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110124192156/http://sportsnavi.yahoo.co.jp/fight/headlines/20110121-00000014-spnavi-fight.html |date=2011-01-24 }}, January 21, 2011, ''[[Yahoo!|Sports Navi \u2013 Yahoo! Japan]]'' {{in lang|ja}}</ref> Simon Rutz, the owner of the [[Netherlands|Dutch]]-based kickboxing promotion [[It's Showtime (kickboxing)|It's Showtime]], claimed in January 2011 that some fighters from It's Showtime had not been paid for fights in K-1.<ref>[http://sportsnavi.yahoo.co.jp/fight/k1/text/201101260006-spnavi_1.html \"What is happening with K-1!? It's Showtime owner Rutz talks about the rumor (1/2)\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120930103229/http://sportsnavi.yahoo.co.jp/fight/k1/text/201101260006-spnavi_1.html |date=2012-09-30 }}, January 21, 2011, ''[[Yahoo!|Sports Navi \u2013 Yahoo! Japan]]'' {{in lang|ja}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2011, [[Fighting and Entertainment Group|FEG]] publicly announced that they were facing financial problems and that the organization would take some months off to restructure. Many fighters and managers spoke out against FEG due to unpaid fight purses and objections to the direction that its owner was taking K-1. It appeared that financial problems were severe, and that FEG could potentially lose ownership of K-1.<ref>[http://news.livedoor.com/article/detail/5289165/ \"K-1 could be purchased after a financial problem!? Like Pride?\"], January 23, 2011, ''[[Livedoor|Livedoor Sports]]'' {{in lang|ja}}</ref>\n\nThe entire K-1 brand, along with most of its trademarks, with the exception of, 'K-1 Koshien', 'K-1 MAX' and '[[Dream (mixed martial arts)|Dream]]', were sold to  Japanese real estate firm, Barbizon Corporation Limited, on July 28, 2011.<ref>[http://www.mmafighting.com/2011/07/28/k-1-sold-to-japanese-real-estate-firm-barbizon/ \"K-1 Sold to Japanese Real Estate Firm Barbizon\"], July 28, 2011, ''[[Aol|MMAFighting]]''</ref>\n\nOn February 1, 2012 EMCOM Entertainment Inc. purchased K-1 from Barbizon.<ref>[http://liverkick.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1258:qmr-kimq-acquires-k-1&catid=36:k-1 K-1 announces agreement with SuperKombat], February 1, 2012, Liver Kick</ref>\n\n===K-1 Global===\nIn March 2012, It's Showtime announced that EMCOM Entertainment established a new company K-1 Global Holdings Ltd. in [[Hong Kong]]. K-1 Global Holdings, Ltd., became the new official owner of the K-1 brand. K-1 Global's agreement with promotion required that certain fighters signed under It's Showtime appear in upcoming K-1 Global events.<ref>[http://www.itsshowtime.nl/index.php?p=news&id=1497 It's Showtime Closes Deal with the New K-1 Organization], March 6, 2012, It's Showtime</ref>\n\nA number of events were already planned and scheduled for the 2012 calendar before new K-1 ownership took complete control of the company. It's Showtime was the promoter of the first event presented by K-1 Global Holdings Ltd., the [[K-1 World MAX 2012 World Championship Tournament Final 16#K-1 World MAX 2012 World Championship Tournament Final 16|K-1 World MAX Final 16]]. It took place on May 27, 2012 at the Palacio Vistalegre in Madrid, Spain.\n\nAfter the event, controversy and rumors circulated over the fact that once again, fighters were not paid for their performances. Problems were compounded due to unpaid financial obligations of FEG, and the complete transfer of ownership of the K-1 name was not yet complete. As a result, the K-1 World Grand Prix scheduled for 2012 would be cancelled if these issues were not resolved.<ref>[http://www.mmafighting.com/2011/10/17/simon-rutz-k-1-world-grand-prix-cancelled-feg-technically-bank Simon Rutz: \"K-1 World Grand Prix Canceled, FEG 'Technically Bankrupt\"], October 17, 2011, Mmafighting.com</ref>\n\nUltimately, K-1 Global Holdings, Ltd. was blamed for the failure of an event they did not promote. They were also accused of not paying fighters when in fact, the promoter and FEG shared responsibilities in ensuring fighters were paid. The Chairman of the new K-1 resolved the matter by paying fighters what was owed and including a 50% bonus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://liverkick.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1260:daniel-ghita-gives-us-insight-into-k-1s-future-and-a-fragmented-kickboxing-world&catid=36:k-1|title=Daniel Ghita gives us insight into K-1's future and a fragmented kickboxing world|publisher=Liverkick.com|accessdate=2015-10-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107065544/http://liverkick.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1260:daniel-ghita-gives-us-insight-into-k-1s-future-and-a-fragmented-kickboxing-world&catid=36:k-1|archive-date=2016-01-07|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIt was announced in June 2012 that It's Showtime was purchased by Glory Sports International, eventually to be merged in their new promotion [[Glory (kickboxing)|GLORY]].<ref>[http://www.gloryworldseries.com/en/news%2F28-glory-world-series-acquires-kickboxing-competitor-it-s-showtime ]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120906055541/http://www.gloryworldseries.com/en/news/28-glory-world-series-acquires-kickboxing-competitor-it-s-showtime |date=September 6, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nOn August 10, 2012 K-1's co-promotion agreement with [[Romania]]n-based kickboxing promotion SUPERKOMBAT was announced.<ref>[http://liverkick.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1774:k-1-announces-agreement-with-superkombat&catid=36:k-1 K-1 announces agreement with SuperKombat], August 10, 2012, Liverkick.com</ref> Eventually it was ended. Early 2013 SK president [[Eduard Irimia]] stated that its company will be independent in 2013 but will still continue to have cooperation with any interested promotion including K-1 by offering fighters.<ref>[http://liverkick.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2310:liverkicks-exclusive-interview-with-superkombat-president-eduard-irimia-pt-1&catid=43:interviews Liverkick's Exclusive Interview with Superkombat President Eduard Irimia], February 19, 2013, Liverkick.com</ref>\n\n===List of K-1 events===\n{{Main|List of K-1 events}}\n{{See also|List of Hero's events}}\n\nIn the past every year there were dozens of other K-1 qualifying tournaments and preliminaries held around the world.\n\nK-1 has held events in many countries around the world.\n\nThe following is a list of countries that K-1 has held events in chronological order:\n*{{flagicon|JPN}} [[Japan]] (1993\u20132012, 2014-2018)\n*{{flagicon|NED}} [[Netherlands]] (1994, 2001\u20132003, 2006\u20132010)\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} [[France]] (1995, 2002\u20132008, 2010)\n*{{flagicon|SWI}} [[Switzerland]] (1995\u20132000, 2003, 2017)\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[United States]] (1998, 2000\u20132008, 2012)\n*{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Australia]] (2000\u20132005, 2010)\n*{{flagicon|ENG}} [[England]] (2000, 2002\u20132004, 2006\u20132007, 2013)\n*{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Italy]] (2000\u20132008)\n*{{flagicon|GER}} [[Germany]] (2000\u20132008)\n*{{flagicon|Belarus}} [[Belarus]] (2000, 2010)\n*{{flagicon|CRO}} [[Croatia]] (2000, 2002, 2007, 2009\u20132010, 2013)\n*{{flagicon|RSA}} [[South Africa]] (2000\u20132002, 2006)\n*{{flagicon|NZ}} New Zealand (2000\u20132006)\n*{{flagicon|Czech Republic}} [[Czech Republic]] (2000\u20132001, 2006\u20132009)\n*{{flagicon|DEN}} [[Denmark]] (2001)\n*{{flagicon|UKR}} [[Ukraine]] (2001\u20132002, 2006, 2010)\n*{{flagicon|ESP}} [[Spain]] (2002\u20132004, 2005\u20132006, 2012\u20132014)\n*{{flagicon|BRA}} [[Brazil]] (2002\u20132006, 2013)\n*{{flagicon|SWE}} [[Sweden]] (2003\u20132010)\n*{{flagicon|RUS}} [[Russia]] (2003, 2006, 2010)\n*{{flagicon|Bosnia}} [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] (2003\u20132004, 2009, 2016)\n*{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Scotland]] (2004)\n*{{flagicon|POR}} [[Portugal]] (2004, 2006, 2013)\n*{{flagicon|POL}} [[Poland]] (2004, 2007\u20132010)\n*{{flagicon|South Korea}} [[South Korea]] (2004\u20132010, 2013)\n*{{flagicon|SLO}} [[Slovenia]] (2005\u20132006, 2008)\n*{{flagicon|HUN}} [[Hungary]] (2005\u20132010)\n*{{flagicon|LIT}} [[Lithuania]] (2006\u20132007, 2010, 2013)\n*{{flagicon|LAT}} [[Latvia]] (2006\u20132008)\n*{{flagicon|TUR}} [[Turkey]] (2007, 2010)\n*{{flagicon|BEL}} [[Belgium]] (2007)\n*{{flagicon|EST}} [[Estonia]] (2007, 2009)\n*{{flagicon|ROM}} [[Romania]] (2007, 2009\u20132010)\n*{{flagicon|Hong Kong}} [[Hong Kong]] (2007)\n*{{flagicon|Austria}} [[Austria]] (2008)\n*{{flagicon|TAI}} [[Taiwan]] (2008)\n*{{flagicon|Moldova}} [[Moldova]] (2009\u20132010, 2013)\n*{{flagicon|China}} [[China]] (2013-2015)\n*{{flagicon|Greece}} [[Greece]] (2012)\n*{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Canada]] (2013)\n*{{flagicon|IRE}} [[Ireland]] (2013)\n*{{flagicon|AZE}} [[Azerbaijan]] (2014)\n*{{flagicon|THA}} [[Thailand]] (2014)\n*{{flagicon|Serbia}} [[Serbia]] (2016)\n\n==Tournament format==\n[[File:K-1 system 2009.jpg|thumb|305px|right|K-1 Qualifying System 2009]]\n\n===K-1 Grand Prix===\n{{Main|K-1 World Grand Prix}}\n\nOriginal K-1 Grand Prix was a single event tournament held in Japan where competitors participated on invitation. By 1998, K-1 introduced the [[K-1 World Grand Prix]] format composed of  K-1 Regional Elimination Tournaments (theoretically amounting to six), which qualify fighters for the K-1 World Grand Prix Final, along with licensed K-1 Fighting Network events designed to hold national preliminaries for regional qualification. However, given the fact that K-1's popularity differs greatly among six K-1 regions, which may limit the number of actual elimination tournaments or change locations. For example, K-1 attempted to gain popularity in the United States by holding two GPs, however only a few Americans have ever qualified for the Finals. In 2006 one of the American GPs was relocated to [[Auckland]]. Additionally the K-1 [[Paris, France|Paris]] GP lost its qualifying right in favor of [[Amsterdam, Netherlands|Amsterdam]]. Eventually Amsterdam lost it in favor of [[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a, Poland|\u0141\u00f3d\u017a]], and then \u0141\u00f3d\u017a in favor of [[Bucharest, Romania|Bucharest]].\n\nK-1 World Grand Prix Final Eliminator (\"Final 16\") is an event where 16 participants compete for the final eight spots in the Final (\"Final 8\"). Eight participants from the Final Eliminator meet at the K-1 World Grand Prix Final. Lesser elements in the tournament format have been significantly modified in years. The final was held at [[Tokyo Dome]] from 1997 to 2006. The 2012 final took place for the first time in history outside Japan, in [[Zagreb, Croatia]].\n\n===K-1 World MAX and other===\nBy 2002, K-1 started the K-1 World MAX (\"Middleweight Artistic Xtreme\") tournament for 70&nbsp;kg (154&nbsp;lb) Middleweight division, following a similar scheme to K-1 World Grand Prix (with theoretically four regional eliminators). In 2007, K-1 introduced two new title belts separate from K-1 World GP Champions, Super Heavyweight World Title for fighters over 100&nbsp;kg/220&nbsp;lbs and Heavyweight World Title for fighters under 100&nbsp;kg/156\u2013220&nbsp;lbs.\n\n==Rules==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=December 2012}}\n*Each match is three or five rounds in duration, with each round lasting three minutes.\n*The match can end by Knockout, Technical Knockout, Decision, Disqualification, Draw or No Contest.\n*Both the referee and the ring doctor have full authority to stop the fight.\n*The fight is scored by three judges on a ten-point must system (The winner of each round receives ten points, and the loser receives nine or less. If the round is even, both competitors receive ten points).\n*If there is a draw after three rounds, the judges' scores are thrown out and one or two extra three-minute rounds are contested. The judges' decision will then come from the scoring of each extra round only. If, after the extra round(s), there is still a draw, the judges will decide a winner based on the flow of the entire match, considering even the slightest difference. A fight can only end in a draw if both fighters go down at the same time and cannot get up, or in the case of accidental injury in the late stages of the contest.\n*Three knockdowns in a round ends the contest, declared a [[technical knockout]].\n*The mandatory eight count is in effect (regardless when the fallen fighter rises, the referee must count to at least \"eight\" on all knockdowns).\n*The standing eight count is in effect (the referee has the right to declare a knockdown on a fighter who appears to be in a dangerous condition to continue in the match).\n*A fighter can be saved by the bell only in the last round.\n\nIn K-1 single elimination tournament matches:\n*Each match is three rounds in duration.\n*Except in the final, two knockdowns in a round ends the contest, declared a [[technical knockout]].\n*One or two reserve fights are held prior to the single elimination matches. If for any reason a fighter who wins and advances through the brackets is unable to continue, a reserve match competitor, or the fighter's opponent from the most recent match, takes his place. There are certain exceptions to this rule (i.e. a fighter who lost a match by knockout might not be eligible to replace another fighter).\n\n===Fouls===\nThe following actions in K-1 are considered fouls:<ref>[http://www.k-1.co.jp/en/what/rules.html]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100809143241/http://www.k-1.co.jp/en/what/rules.html |date=August 9, 2010 }}</ref>\n*Using the head or elbow to deliver a blow\n*Attacking the opponent in the groin\n*Delivering wrestling or judo throwing or submission techniques\n*Thumbing, choking or biting the opponent\n*Punching the opponent in the throat\n*Attacking the opponent while he is down or in the process of getting up\n*Attacking the opponent after the referee calls a break\n*Holding the ropes\n*Using offensive language to the referee\n*Attacking the back of the head with a punch\n*Attempting to cause the opponent to fall out of the ring\n*Voluntarily exiting the ring during the course of a match\n*Attacking an opponent who turns around and shows his back (if the opponent loses his will to fight)\n*Delivering a backspin blow in an unauthorized area\n*Charging inside the opponent's arms with the head held low (inducing a head-butt)\n*Fighting in a passive manner (without attacking), including continuous holding and clinching\n*Attacking more than once while holding the opponent's kicking leg, or while holding the opponent's neck with both hands\n\nA fighter is penalized as follows:\n*Caution&nbsp;\u2013 verbal reprimand by the referee\n*Warning&nbsp;\u2013 fighter is shown a yellow card\n*Point Deduction&nbsp;\u2013 fighter is shown a red card\n\nTwo cautions result in one warning. Two warnings result in a point deduction, and three point deductions in one round can result in a disqualification.\n\nA red card is shown automatically if a fighter commits a foul with malicious intent.\n\n==Popularity/Media==\nKickboxing is very popular in [[Japan]], [[South Korea]], [[Brazil]], and in [[Europe]] in countries such as the [[Netherlands]], [[Croatia]] and [[Romania]] but recently enjoys only limited popularity in the [[United States]].\n\nIn the past the events were frequently shown on [[Tokyo Broadcasting System]] and [[Fuji Television|Fuji TV]]<ref name=\"headkicklegend\">{{cite web|url=http://www.headkicklegend.com/2010/3/31/1398385/k-1-world-grand-prix-yokohama-to|title=Bad Left Hook, Global Boxing News and Commentary|publisher=Headkicklegend.com|accessdate=2014-04-06}}</ref> in Japan, XTM in South Korea, Combate and [[SporTV]] in Brazil, [[HDNet Fights]]<ref>[http://www.sherdog.com/news/press%20releases/k-1-to-air-on-hdnet-15257 ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091029042332/http://www.sherdog.com/news/press%20releases/k-1-to-air-on-hdnet-15257 |date=October 29, 2009 }}</ref> in the United States and on [[Eurosport]] in Europe.\n\nAfter the 'Katougi boom', and the loss of a mainstream network deal, [[AbemaTV]] became K-1's primary broadcaster.<ref>https://abema.tv/timetable</ref> K-1 Japan Group also operates a YouTube channel where fights, press conferences, and general media is uploaded.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/user/k1WorldLeague</ref>\n\n==List of K-1 champions==\n{{main|List of K-1 champions}}\n\n===Current champions===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Division!!Champion!!Since!!Title defences\n|-\n| [[Super Heavyweight]]  || {{flagicon|NED}} [[Roel Mannaart]]  || 2018 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1\n|-\n| [[Cruiserweight]] (-90&nbsp;kg) ||{{flagicon|Iran}} [[Sina Karimian]]|| 2019 ||style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2\n|-\n| [[Super Welterweight]] (-70&nbsp;kg) || {{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Minoru Kimura]] || 2020 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 0\n|-\n| [[Welterweight]] (-67.5&nbsp;kg) || {{flagicon|JPN}} [[Yuta Kubo]] || 2017 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 3\n|-\n| [[Super Lightweight]] (-65&nbsp;kg) || {{flagicon|JPN}} [[Rukiya Anpo]] || 2019 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2\n|-\n| [[Lightweight]] (-62.5&nbsp;kg) || {{flagicon|JPN}} [[Kenta Hayashi]] || 2019 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 0\n|-\n| [[Super Featherweight]] (-60&nbsp;kg) || {{flagicon|JPN}} [[Takeru Segawa]] || 2017 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1\n|-\n| [[Featherweight]] (-57.5&nbsp;kg) || {{flagicon|JPN}} [[Yuki Egawa]] || 2019 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 0\n|-\n| [[Super Bantamweight]] (-55&nbsp;kg) || {{flagicon|JPN}} [[Yoshiki Takei]] || 2017 || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Martial arts}}\n*[[List of K-1 events]]\n*[[List of K-1 champions]]\n*[[List of male kickboxers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.k-1world.com/}}\n*[https://www.k-1.co.jp/ K-1 Japan]\n\n{{Kickboxing organizations}}\n{{Martial arts}}\n\n[[Category:K-1| ]]\n[[Category:Kickboxing organizations]]\n[[Category:Sports organizations established in 1993]]\n[[Category:1993 establishments in Japan]]\n[[Category:Kickboxing in Japan]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toCruiserweight(link changed toCruiserweight (MMA)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/K-1"}
{"title_page": "Lord Randolph Churchill", "text_new": "{{short description|British politician}}\n{{about||the son of Sir Winston Churchill|Randolph Churchill|the biography|Lord Randolph Churchill (book)}}\n{{British barrelled name unused|[[Spencer-Churchill]]|Churchill}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = Lord Randolph Churchill\n|honorific-suffix =\n|image            = Lord Randolph Churchill.jpg\n|imagesize        = \n|smallimage       =\n|caption          =\n|order            = [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]]\n|term_start       = 3 August 1886\n|term_end         = 22 December 1886\n|primeminister    = [[Robert Cecil, 3rd Marquess of Salisbury|The Marquess of Salisbury]]\n|predecessor      = [[William Vernon Harcourt (politician)|William Vernon Harcourt]]\n|successor        = [[George Goschen, 1st Viscount Goschen|George Goschen]]\n|order2           = [[Leader of the House of Commons]]\n|term_start2      = 3 August 1886\n|term_end2        = 14 January 1887\n|primeminister2   = [[Robert Cecil, 3rd Marquess of Salisbury|The Marquess of Salisbury]]\n|predecessor2     = [[William Ewart Gladstone]]\n|successor2       = [[William Henry Smith (1825\u20131891)|William Henry Smith]]\n|office3          = [[Secretary of State for India]]\n|term_start3      = 24 June 1885\n|term_end3        = 28 January 1886\n|primeminister3   = [[Robert Cecil, 3rd Marquess of Salisbury|The Marquess of Salisbury]]\n|preceded3        = [[John Wodehouse, 1st Earl of Kimberley|The Earl of Kimberley]]\n|succeeded3       = [[John Wodehouse, 1st Earl of Kimberley|The Earl of Kimberley]]\n|birth_name       = Randolph Henry Spencer-Churchill\n|birth_date       = 13 February 1849\n|birth_place      = [[Belgravia]], [[London]], England\n|death_date       = {{death date and age|1895|1|24|1849|2|13|df=yes}}\n|death_place      = [[Westminster]], London, England\n|party            = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|spouse           = {{marriage|[[Lady Randolph Churchill|Jennie Jerome]]|15 April 1874}}\n|children         = [[Winston Churchill|Sir Winston Spencer-Churchill]]<br/>[[John Strange Spencer-Churchill|John Spencer-Churchill]]\n|parents          = [[John Spencer-Churchill, 7th Duke of Marlborough]]<br/>[[Frances Anne Spencer-Churchill, Duchess of Marlborough|Lady Frances Anne Vane]]\n|profession       = Politician\n|alma_mater       = [[Merton College, Oxford]]\n}}\n\n'''Lord Randolph Henry Spencer-Churchill''' (13 February 1849 \u2013 24 January 1895) was a British statesman.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Lord-Randolph-Churchill-British-politician |title=Lord Randolph Churchill {{!}} British politician |website=Encyclopedia Britannica |language=en |access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref> Churchill was a [[Tory]] radical and coined the term '[[One-nation conservatism|Tory democracy]]'.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Quinault |first=R.E. |date=March 1979 |title=Lord Randolph Churchill and Tory Democracy, 1880\u20131885 |url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/historical-journal/article/lord-randolph-churchill-and-tory-democracy-18801885/E2FA5614DFCC64D5E6F77DDC8F926720 |journal=The Historical Journal |language=en |volume=22 |issue=1 |pages=141\u2013165 |doi=10.1017/S0018246X0001671X |issn=0018-246X}}</ref> He inspired a generation of party managers, created the National Union of the Conservative Party, and broke new ground in modern budgetary presentations, attracting admiration and criticism from across the political spectrum. His most acerbic critics were in his own party, among his closest friends; but his disloyalty to [[Lord Salisbury]] was the beginning of the end of what should have been a glittering career.  His elder son, [[Winston Churchill|Winston]], wrote a biography of him in 1906.<ref>Churchill, Winston C. 1906. ''Lord Randolph Churchill''. 2 vols, Macmillan, London.</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Lord Randolph Churchill by Hills and Saunders, 1860s.jpg|150px|thumb|left|Churchill in the 1860s]]\nBorn at 3 [[Wilton Terrace]], [[Belgravia]], London, Randolph Spencer was the third son of [[John Spencer-Churchill, 7th Duke of Marlborough|John Spencer-Churchill, Marquess of Blandford]], and his wife the Marchioness of Blandford (''[[n\u00e9e]]'' [[Frances Anne Spencer-Churchill, Duchess of Marlborough|Lady Frances Vane]]); upon John's father's death in 1857, they became the (7th) Duke of Marlborough, and the Duchess of Marlborough, respectively.<ref name=\"ODNB\">{{cite ODNB|id=5404|title=Churchill, Lord Randolph Henry Spencer|first=Roland|last=Quinault}}</ref> As the younger son of a Marquess, Randolph had a [[Courtesy titles in the United Kingdom|courtesy title]], and was ''Lord Randolph Churchill''; but was a commoner able to sit in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]].\n\nChurchill attended [[Cheam School|Tabor's Preparatory School, Cheam]], then in 1863 [[Eton College]], where he remained until 1865.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/> He did not stand out either at academic work or sport while at Eton; his contemporaries describe him as a vivacious and rather unruly boy.{{sfn|Low|1911|p=346}} Among the lifelong friendships he made at school were with [[Arthur Balfour]] and [[Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery|Archibald Primrose]] (later Lord Rosebery).<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>  \n\nIn October 1867, Churchill matriculated at [[Merton College, Oxford]]. At Oxford, Primrose \u2013 now with his own courtesy title of ''Lord Dalmeny'' \u2013 was along with Churchill a member of the [[Bullingdon Club]], and joined him at the Club's champagne-fuelled parties.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">[[Frank Harris]], ''[[My Life and Loves]]'', 1922\u201327; p. 483</ref> Randolph was frequently in trouble with the university authorities for drunkenness, smoking in academic dress, and smashing windows at the [[Randolph Hotel, Oxford|Randolph Hotel]]. His rowdy behaviour was infectious, rubbing off on friends and contemporaries; he gained a reputation as an ''[[enfant terrible]]''.<ref>[[Leo McKinstry]], ''Rosebery: Statesman in Turmoil'', pp. 23, 33</ref> He had a liking for hunting, but was also a well-read historian. He gaining a second-class degree in [[jurisprudence]] and modern history in 1870.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/> \n\nChurchill experienced none of the early doubts but made many mistakes, as alluded to in Rosebery's biography.<ref>Rosebery, Ld Randolph, (1906);[[Leo McKinstry]], ''Rosebery: Statesman in Turmoil'', p. 58</ref> He never regretted being an early friend and admirer of the Disraelis. His behaviour was, however, the later cause of dissension in his relations with a colder, more aloof, disciplinarian [[Lord Salisbury|Salisbury]]. In 1871 Churchill and his elder brother [[George Spencer-Churchill, 8th Duke of Marlborough|George]] were initiated into the rites of [[Freemasonry]], as later his son Winston would be.<ref>{{cite web |last=Churchill |first=Randolph |title=Masonic Papers |url=http://www.freemasons-freemasonry.com/freemasonry_england.html |work=The Development of the Craft in England |publisher=freemasons-freemasonary.com |accessdate=30 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nAt the general election of 1874 Churchill was elected to Parliament as [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] member for [[Woodstock (UK Parliament constituency)|Woodstock]], near the family seat, defeating [[George Charles Brodrick|George Brodrick]], a Fellow of Merton. His [[maiden speech]], delivered in his first session, prompted compliments from [[William Vernon Harcourt (politician)|William Harcourt]] and [[Benjamin Disraeli]], who wrote to the Queen of Churchill's \"energy and natural flow\".<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>\n\nChurchill was a close friend of [[Nathan Rothschild, 1st Baron Rothschild]], and received \"extensive loans\" from the Rothschilds. He reported on the mining industry in South Africa on their behalf, where their agent [[Cecil Rhodes]] was consolidating mining deposits which ultimately led to the creation of [[De Beers]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rothschildarchive.org/business/rothschild_clients |title=The Rothschild Archive |website=rothschildarchive.org |accessdate=24 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Marriage and medical condition==\n[[File:Lord Randolph Churchill and Lady Jennie Jerome (1874) (A).jpg|thumb|right|upright=|Lord Randolph Churchill and [[Lady Randolph Churchill]] (Jennie Jerome) in [[Paris]] (1874) by [[Georges Penabert]]]]\n\nLord Randolph Churchill was married at the [[Embassy of the United Kingdom, Paris|British Embassy in Paris]] on 15 April 1874 to [[Lady Randolph Churchill|Jennie Jerome]], daughter of [[Leonard Jerome]], an American businessman.<ref>Anita Leslie. ''Jennie: The Life of Lady Randolph Churchill'', 1969</ref> The couple had two sons:\n*[[Winston Churchill|Winston Leonard Spencer-Churchill]] (30 November 1874{{snd}}24 January 1965)\n*[[Jack Churchill (1880\u20131947)|John Strange \"Jack\" Spencer-Churchill]] (4 February 1880{{snd}}23 February 1947)\n\nIn January 1875, about a month after Winston's birth, Randolph made repeated visits to Dr [[Oscar Clayton]].<ref name=\"Morgan\">Ted Morgan, ''Churchill: Young Man in a Hurry, 1874\u20131915'' (1984), p. 23</ref> He had twenty years to live, but suffered from debilitating illness, particularly in his last decade. Quinault writing in the ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'' considers that he probably was passing through the stages of [[secondary syphilis]] and then [[tertiary syphilis]], but mentions a [[brain tumour]] and [[multiple sclerosis]] as other possible causes.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/> It is definitely the case that he was treated for [[syphilis]], and it has been suggested that he was suffering from symptoms of the [[mercury (element)|mercury]]-based medication.<ref name=\"Foster\">{{cite book |first=R. F. |last=Foster |title=Lord Randolph Churchill: A Political Life |authorlink=R. F. Foster (historian) |page=218 |date=1988}}</ref> Clayton was a society doctor and specialist in the treatment of syphilis at his London practice at 5,{{nbsp}}[[Harley Street]].<ref name=\"Morgan\"/> [[Robson Roose]], who was the Churchills' family doctor in the 1880s, had written on syphilis, his diagnosis, as a root cause of debilitating disease. He referred Randolph to the specialist [[Thomas Buzzard]], but continued to prescribe [[potassium iodide]] and mercury.<ref name=\"Foster\"/>\n\nAccording to [[Frank Harris]], who published the allegation in his scandalous autobiography, ''[[My Life and Loves]]'' (1922\u201327), \"Randolph had caught syphilis...\" <ref name=\"Morgan\"/> He relied on a story by [[Louis Jennings]], an associate of Randolph's who had later fallen out with him. John H. Mather of the [[National Churchill Library and Center]] called into question Harris' veracity and offered the alternative theory of a \"left side brain tumour\". Mather noted that \"There is no indication that Lady Randolph or her sons were infected with syphilis.\"<ref name=\"maladiesetmort\">{{cite news|url=http://www.winstonchurchill.org/resources/myths/144-lord-randolph-churchill-maladies-et-mort|title=Lord Randolph Churchill: Maladies et Mort|accessdate=17 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===The \"Fourth Party\"===\n[[File:The Fourth Party Vanity Fair 1 December 1880.jpg|thumb|left|<center>\"The Fourth Party\" Spencer-Churchill, Balfour, Drummond-Wolff and Gorst as caricatured by Spy ([[Leslie Ward]]) in ''[[Vanity Fair (British magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', 1 December 1880</center>]]\nIt was not until 1878 that he came to public notice as the exponent of independent Conservatism. He made a series of furious attacks on [[Sir Stafford Northcote]], [[Richard Assheton Cross, 1st Viscount Cross|R. A. Cross]], and other prominent members of the \"old gang\". [[George Sclater-Booth, 1st Baron Basing|George Sclater-Booth]] (afterwards 1st Baron Basing), [[President of the Local Government Board]], was a specific target, and the minister's County Government Bill was fiercely denounced as the \"crowning dishonour to Tory principles\", and the \"supreme violation of political honesty\".{{sfn|Low|1911|p=346}} Lord Randolph's attitude, and the vituperative fluency of his invective, made him a parliamentary figure of some importance before the dissolution of the 1874 parliament, though he was not yet taken quite seriously, owing to his high-pitched hysterical laugh.<ref>Blake, pp. 134-35</ref>\n\nIn the new parliament of 1880 he speedily began to play a more notable role. Along with [[Henry Drummond Wolff]], [[John Eldon Gorst|John Gorst]] and occasionally [[Arthur Balfour]], he made himself known as the audacious opponent of the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] administration and the unsparing critic of the Conservative front bench. The \"fourth party\", as it was nicknamed, at first did little damage to the government, but awakened the opposition from its apathy; Churchill roused the Conservatives by leading resistance to [[Charles Bradlaugh]], the member for [[Northampton (UK Parliament constituency)|Northampton]], who, an avowed atheist or agnostic, was prepared to take the parliamentary oath under protest. Stafford Northcote, the Conservative leader in the Lower House, was forced to take a strong line on this difficult question by the energy of the fourth party.{{sfn|Low|1911|p=346}}\n\nThe long controversy over Bradlaugh's seat showed that Lord Randolph Churchill was a parliamentary champion who added to his audacity much tactical skill and shrewdness. He continued to play a conspicuous part throughout the parliament of 1880\u201385, targeting [[William Ewart Gladstone]] as well as the Conservative front bench, some of whose members, particularly [[R. A. Cross, 1st Viscount Cross|Sir Richard Cross]] and [[William Henry Smith (1825\u20131891)|William Henry Smith]], he singled out for attack when they opposed the reduced Army estimates.{{sfn|Low|1911|p=346}} This would be the ostensible cause for his resignation because Salisbury failed to support his Chancellor in cabinet. They opposed his unionist politics of 'economising' by Tory tradition, making Randolph grow to hate cabinet meetings.<ref>W S Churchill, ''Life of Lord Randolph Churchill'', 2 vols, chap XIV<!-- publisher, ISSN/ISBN, page(s) needed --></ref>\n\nFrom the beginning of the [[History of Modern Egypt|Egyptian]] imbroglio Lord Randolph was emphatically opposed to almost every step taken by the government. He declared that the suppression of [[\u2018Urabi Revolt|Urabi Pasha's rebellion]] was an error, and the restoration of the [[khedive]]'s authority a crime. He called Gladstone the \"[[Moloch]] of [[Midlothian (UK Parliament constituency) (1708\u20131918)|Midlothian]]\", for whom torrents of blood had been shed in Africa. He was equally severe on the domestic policy of the administration, and was particularly bitter in his criticism of the [[Kilmainham Treaty]] and the rapprochement between the Gladstonians and the [[Charles Stewart Parnell|Parnellites]].{{sfn|Low|1911|p=346}}\n\n===Tory Democracy===\n[[File:Randolph Churchill.jpg|200px|right|thumb|Lord Randolph Churchill]]\nBy 1885 he had formulated the policy of progressive Conservatism which was known as \"[[Tory Democracy]]\". He declared that the Conservatives ought to adopt, rather than oppose, popular reforms, and to challenge the claims of the Liberals to pose as champions of the masses. His views were largely accepted by the official Conservative leaders in the treatment of the Gladstonian [[Representation of the People Act 1884]]. Lord Randolph insisted that the principle of the bill should be accepted by the opposition, and that resistance should be focused on the refusal of the government to combine with it a scheme of redistribution. The prominent, and on the whole judicious and successful, part he played in the debates on these questions, still further increased his influence with the rank and file of the Conservatives in the constituencies.{{sfn|Low|1911|p=346}}\n\nAt the same time he was actively spreading his gospel of democratic Toryism in a series of platform campaigns. In 1883 and 1884 he went to the radical stronghold of [[Birmingham]], and in the latter year took part in a Conservative garden party at Aston Manor, at which his opponents paid him the compliment of raising a serious riot. He gave constant attention to the party organisation, which had fallen into considerable disorder after 1880, and was an active promoter of the [[Primrose League]], which owed its origin to the inspiration of one of his own \u201cfourth party\u201d colleagues.{{sfn|Low|1911|p=346}}\n\n===Central Office and National Union===\nIn 1884 progressive Toryism won out. At the conference of the [[National Union of Conservative Associations]], Lord Randolph was nominated chairman, despite the opposition of the parliamentary leaders.  A split was averted by Lord Randolph's voluntary resignation which he had done his best to engineer; but the episode had confirmed his title to a leading place in the Tory ranks.{{sfn|Low|1911|p=346}}<ref>Blake, p. 145</ref>\n\nHe built up Tory Democracy in the towns reinforcing the urban middle classes part in the party, while simultaneously including a working-class element.  His unsuccessful bid for the party leadership was inextricably part of the National Union's attempt to control the party organization.<ref>Blake, p. 152</ref> It had originally been founded by Tory peers to organize propaganda to attract working men's votes, registration, choose candidates, conduct elections; associations were linked to provincial unions. Lord Randolph was not the originator but his campaign of 1884 encouraged the leadership to improve on their designs. For the first time since 1832 the Conservatives won in the majority of English boroughs in November 1885.<ref>R.R. James; Blake, pp. 152-53</ref>\n\nIt was strengthened by the prominent part he played in the events immediately preceding the fall of the Liberal government in 1885; and when [[Hugh Childers]]'s budget resolutions were defeated by the Conservatives, aided by about half the Parnellites, Lord Randolph Churchill's admirers were justified in proclaiming him to have been the \"organiser of victory\".{{sfn|Low|1911|p=346}}\n\n===Secretary of State for India===\nIn Lord Salisbury's \"caretaker\" cabinet of 1885, Churchill was appointed [[Secretary of State for India]], assuming office on 24{{nbsp}}June 1885.<ref name=DIB>[[s:Dictionary of Indian Biography/Churchill, Lord Randolph Henry Spencer]]</ref> As the price of entry he demanded that Sir Stafford Northcote be removed from the Commons, despite being the Conservative leader there. Salisbury was more than willing to concede this, and Northcote went to the Lords as the Earl of Iddlesleigh.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\nDespite entering office with a reputation for progressive views on India, Churchill 's tenure was, in the words of the historian and biographer R.F. Foster, 'traditionally reactionary', and many of his policies focused on exploiting, not developing India.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Foster |first1=R.F. |title=Lord Randolph Churchill: A Political Life |date=1981 |publisher=Oxford University Press |page=168}}</ref> He enthusiastically supported a trade policy which favoured British imports over Indian goods; increased spending on the Indian Army at the expense of public works such as railways, roads and irrigation (all sharply reduced under his secretaryship); and re-directed money which had been set aside for future famine relief to help balance his budget.<ref>Foster, ''Randolph Churchill'', pp. 189-190, 193-194</ref> His attitude towards the native Indians was similarly illiberal. He refused to allow reforms which would have increased Indian representation within the civil service and army, and, in a public speech at Birmingham, he infamously described a deputation to Britain by three Indian politicians, led by [[N. G. Chandavarkar]], as the 'three Bengalee baboos'.<ref>Foster, ''Randolph Churchill'', pp. 193, 204-205</ref> \n\nHowever, Churchill's most well-known act during his time at the India Office was his role in the invasion and annexation of Burma in the [[Third Anglo-Burmese War]].<ref>Kwarsi Kwarteng, ''Ghosts of Empire: Britain's Legacies in the Modern World'', Bloomsbury, 2011, Part III</ref> Siding with British commercial (especially cotton) and military interests, and hoping to boost Conservative fortunes in the upcoming general election, Churchill directed the [[Viceroy]], [[Frederick Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 1st Marquess of Dufferin and Ava|Lord Dufferin]], to invade [[Upper Burma]] in November 1885.<ref>Foster, ''Randolph Churchill'', pp. 206-213</ref> With little discussion, Churchill then decided to annex the Burmese kingdom, adding it as a new province of the Indian [[British Raj|Raj]] as a \"New Year present\" for [[Queen Victoria]] on New Year's Day 1886. Not only is the war itself widely regarded as a piece of blatant [[imperialism]], but the continuing guerrilla war lasted into the later 1880s and cost the Indian taxpayer ten times Churchill's original financial estimates.<ref>Foster, ''Randolph Churchill'', p. 209</ref> \n\nIn the autumn election of 1885 he contested [[Birmingham Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Birmingham Central]] against [[John Bright]], and though defeated here, was at the same time returned by a very large majority for [[Paddington South (UK Parliament constituency)|South Paddington]].{{sfn|Low|1911|p=346}}\n\nIn the contest which arose over [[William Ewart Gladstone]]'s [[First Irish Home Rule Bill|Home Rule]] bill, Lord Randolph again bore a conspicuous part, and in the electioneering campaign his activity was only second to that of some of the [[Liberal Unionist Party|Liberal Unionists]], [[Spencer Cavendish, 8th Duke of Devonshire|Lord Hartington]], [[George Joachim Goschen, 1st Viscount Goschen|George Goschen]] and [[Joseph Chamberlain]]. He was now the recognised Conservative champion in the Lower Chamber, and when the second Salisbury administration was formed after the general election of 1886 he became [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] and [[Leader of the House of Commons]].{{sfn|Low|1911|p=346}}\n\n===End of political career===\n[[File:Edward Linley Sambourne - Lord Randolph Churchill, 1881.png|thumb|upright|1881 [[Punch (magazine)|''Punch'']] cartoon by [[Edward Linley Sambourne]] of Lord Randolph Churchill, M.P., as a \"midge with no sting in Parliament.\"]]\n\nChurchill was new to the leadership ranks, and became a relatively isolated figure in the cabinet. He did not think in terms of consulting his supporters and building a base in Commons; instead, he decided to use his strong public support to impose his positions on Prime Minister Lord Salisbury in both domestic and foreign affairs. He decided to demonstrate to the public that the Conservatives could be as economical in budgetary matters as Gladstone had been. Therefore, he proposed a budget with significant slashes that surprised and annoyed the Conservative MPs. They were willing to compromise, but he insisted on additional cuts in the Army and Navy that alarmed the service ministers. Churchill decided to threaten resignation\u2014it proved one of the great blunders in British political history. In his resignation letter he stated that it was because he was unable as Chancellor to support the service. He expected his resignation to be followed by the unconditional surrender of the cabinet, and his restoration to office on his own terms. Instead, Salisbury accepted the resignation, and Churchill was out in the cold. Goschen replaced him as Chancellor.<ref>Norman McCord and Bill Purdue, ''British History, 1815-1914'' (2nd ed. 2007) pp 410-11,.</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=Eric Alexander |title=Chief Whip |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NP7lDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT88 |year=1961 |pages=86\u201389 |isbn=9781442654655}}</ref> For the next few years there was some speculation about a return to front-line politics, but Churchill's own career was over.{{sfn|Low|1911|p=347}} Even so, his economising ideas survived yet in the \"Dartford Programme\" of September 1886.\n\nAlthough Lord Randolph continued to sit in Parliament, his health was in serious decline throughout the 1890s. He was an ardent patron of horse-racing and in 1889, his horse [[L'Abbesse de Jouarre]] won [[Epsom Oaks|The Oaks]]. In 1891 he went to South Africa, in search both of health and relaxation. He travelled for some months through [[Cape Colony]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.matjiesfontein.com/About/index.htm |title=Matjiesfontein History - Matjiesfontein |website=matjiesfontein.com |accessdate=24 July 2017}}</ref> the [[South African Republic|Transvaal]] and [[Rhodesia]], making notes on the politics and economics of the countries, shooting lions, and recording his impressions in letters to a London newspaper, which were afterwards republished under the title of ''Men, Mines and Animals in South Africa''. He attacked [[William Ewart Gladstone|Gladstone]]'s [[Second Irish Home Rule Bill|Second Home Rule Bill]] with energy,{{sfn|Low|1911|p=347}} and gave fiery pro-Union speeches in Ireland.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} During this time he coined the phrase \"Ulster will fight, and Ulster will be right\", echoing his earlier remark that in opposing Irish Home Rule \"the Orange card would be the one to play\".<ref>{{cite book |author=Paul Bew |title=Churchill and Ireland |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UzrcCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT55 |year=2016 |publisher=Oxford University Press |pages=55\u201356 |isbn=9780191071492}}</ref>\n\nIt was soon apparent that Churchill's powers had been undermined by the illness which was to take his life at the age of 45. As the session of 1893 wore on, his speeches lost their old effectiveness. His last speech in the House was delivered in the debate on the East African Scheme in June 1894, and was a painful failure.{{sfn|Low|1911|p=347}}\n\n==Death==\nAn attempted round-the-world journey failed to cure Lord Randolph of his debilitating illness. He started in the autumn of 1894, accompanied by his wife, but his health soon became so feeble that he was brought back hurriedly from Cairo. He reached England shortly before Christmas, and died in [[Westminster]].{{sfn|Low|1911|p=347}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=cnS1ua%2FEVI2BXjrLIgIY7Q&scan=1 |title=Index entry |access-date=24 April 2018 |work=[[FreeBMD]] |publisher=ONS}}</ref> The gross value of his personal estate was entered in the Probate Registry at \u00a375,971.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9C01E5DF133DE433A25756C0A9659C94649ED7CF |title=RANDOLPH CHURCHILL'S WILL; Details of the Estate Bequeathed to His Wife and Children |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=5 March 1895 |page=5 |access-date=25 July 2019 |publisher=[[The New York Times Company]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090222031341/http://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9C01E5DF133DE433A25756C0A9659C94649ED7CF |archive-date=22 February 2009}}</ref> This is the financial equivalent of over \u00a38.34 million in 2018 terms, using the retail price index.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.measuringworth.com/ppoweruk/result.php?use%5B%5D=CPI&use%5B%5D=NOMINALEARN&year_early=1894&pound71=76&shilling71=&pence71=&amount=76&year_source=1894&year_result=2010r |work=Measuring Worth \u2013 Measures of worth, inflation rates, saving calculator, relative value, worth of a dollar, worth of a pound, purchasing power, gold prices, GDP... |access-date=16 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610220910/http://www.measuringworth.com/ppoweruk/result.php?use%5B%5D=CPI&use%5B%5D=NOMINALEARN&year_early=1894&pound71=76&shilling71=&pence71=&amount=76&year_source=1894&year_result=2010r |archive-date=10 June 2015 |title=Purchasing Power of British Pounds from 1245 to Present |first=Lawrence H. |last=Officer |first2=Samuel H. |last2=Williamson |year=2012}}</ref> He is buried near his wife and sons at [[St Martin's Church, Bladon]], near [[Woodstock, Oxfordshire]].\n\nHis widow, Lady Randolph Churchill, married [[George Cornwallis-West]] in 1900, when she became known as Mrs. George Cornwallis-West.  After that marriage was dissolved, she resumed by [[deed poll]] her prior married name, Lady Randolph Churchill. (Lord Randolph was her husband's courtesy title as the younger son of a duke and in English law does not qualify as a noble title in its own right.) Lord Randolph's son, Sir [[Winston Churchill]], died on 24 January 1965, aged 90, exactly 70 years after the death of his father, having lived twice as long.\n\n==Personality and reputation==\nRosebery described his old friend and political opponent, after his death, thus: \"his nervous system was always tense and highly strung; ...he seems to have had no knowledge  of men, no consideration of their feelings, no give and take.\"  But he continued, \"in congenial society, his conversation was wholly delightful. He would then display his mastery of pleasant irony and banter; for with those playthings he was at his best.\"<ref>Gertrude Atherton, ''Review: Lord Randolph Churchill'', Reviewed Work: Lord Randolph Churchill by Lord Rosebery, The North American Review Vol. 184, No. 606 (Jan. 4, 1907), pp. 87\u201391, at p. 90. (5 pages) Published by: University of Northern Iowa {{jstor|25105753}}</ref>\n\nBiographer [[Roy Jenkins]], pointing to his brash and slightly vulgar charisma, asked, \"Was he ever near to being a serious statesman?\":\n\n<blockquote>Undoubtedly, he had some high political talents. He had a gift for mordant, wounding, sometimes very funny phrases. And, having thought up the most outrageous attack he had the nerve to deliver it, without fear of offending taste or friends or damaging his own repute....He was strong on insolence. He also had other attributes necessary to make his words resound, and his fame increase: a mnemonic name, an  idiosyncratic appearance, and good delivery, whether on the platform or in the House of Commons. In addition he had sporadic charm, although intermingled with offensive and often pointless rudeness.<ref>Roy Jenkins, ''The Chancellors'' (1998), pp. 11-12.</ref></blockquote>\n\nJenkins compares his youth to that of [[William Pitt the Younger]]: \"Pitt was Prime Minister for 19 of his 46 years. Churchill had 11 months in office and was without rival in attracting so much attention and achieving so little.\"<ref>Jenkins, ''The Chancellors'' (1998) p. 36.</ref>\n\n==Family==\n;Parents\n*[[John Spencer-Churchill, 7th Duke of Marlborough]]\n*[[Frances Anne Spencer-Churchill, Duchess of Marlborough|Lady Frances Anne Emily Vane]] (15 April 1822{{snd}}16 April 1899), the eldest daughter of the [[Charles William Vane, 3rd Marquess of Londonderry|3rd Marquess of Londonderry]] and Lady [[Frances Anne Vane, Marchioness of Londonderry|Frances Anne Emily Vane-Tempest]].\n;Siblings\n*[[George Spencer-Churchill, 8th Duke of Marlborough|George Charles Spencer-Churchill, 8th Duke of Marlborough]] (13 May 1844{{snd}}9 November 1892)\n*Lord Frederick John Winston Spencer-Churchill (2 February 1846{{snd}}5 August 1850)\n*[[Lady Cornelia Henrietta Maria Spencer-Churchill]] (17 September 1847{{snd}}[[Mayfair|Upper Brook Street, Mayfair, London]], 22 January 1927), married 25 May 1868 [[Ivor Bertie Guest, 1st Baron Wimborne]], by whom she had issue.\n*[[Lady Rosamund Jane Frances Spencer-Churchill]] (1851\u2013 3 December 1920), married 12 July 1877 [[William Fellowes, 2nd Baron de Ramsey]], by whom she had issue\n*[[Lady Fanny Octavia Louise Spencer-Churchill]] (29 January 1853{{snd}}5 August 1904), married 9 June 1873 [[Edward Marjoribanks, 2nd Baron Tweedmouth]], by whom she had issue.\n*[[Anne Innes-Ker, Duchess of Roxburghe|Lady Anne Emily Spencer-Churchill]] ([[Mayfair|Lower Brook Street, Mayfair, London]], 14 November 1854{{snd}}[[Mayfair|South Audley Street, Mayfair, London]], 20 June 1923), married 11 June 1874 [[James Innes-Ker, 7th Duke of Roxburghe]], by whom she had issue.\n*Lord Charles Ashley Spencer-Churchill (1856{{snd}}11 March 1858)\n*Lord Augustus Robert Spencer-Churchill (4 July 1858{{snd}}12 May 1859)\n*[[Lady Georgiana Elizabeth Spencer-Churchill]] (10 [[St James's Square]], St James's, London, 14 May 1860{{snd}}9 February 1906), married 4 June 1883 [[Richard Curzon, 4th Earl Howe|Richard George Penn Curzon, 4th Earl Howe]], by whom she had issue.\n*[[Lady Sarah Wilson|Lady Sarah Isabella Augusta Spencer-Churchill]] (1865{{snd}}22 October 1929), a war correspondent during the [[Boer War]]; married 21 November 1891 Lt. Col. Gordon Chesney Wilson (son of Sir Samuel Wilson, MP)\n;Spouse\n*[[Lady Randolph Churchill|Jennie Jerome]]\n;Children\n*[[Winston Churchill|Sir Winston Churchill]]\n*[[Jack Churchill (1880\u20131947)|John Strange Spencer-Churchill]]\n\n==Film, television and literary depictions==\nIn the ITV historical drama series ''[[Edward the Seventh]]'', Lord Randolph (played by [[Derek Fowlds]]) is featured as a more natural character, sociably similar to [[Edward VII of the United Kingdom|Albert Edward, Prince of Wales]] and his other friends. His downfall is represented when he confronts [[Alexandra of Denmark|Alexandra, Princess of Wales]] and demands she use her influence with the Prince to stop [[Lord Aylesford]] proceeding with a divorce from his wife, Lady Aylesford, after she had planned to elope with Lord Randolph's elder brother, the [[George Spencer-Churchill, 8th Duke of Marlborough|Marquess of Blandford]]. He threatens to expose letters from the Prince to Lady Aylesford, so scandalous, so he says, that if they were to be exposed, \"the Prince of Wales would never sit on the throne of England.\"\n\nOutraged, the Princess goes to see the [[Queen Victoria|Queen]], who is equally indignant. Prime Minister [[Benjamin Disraeli, 1st Earl of Beaconsfield|Benjamin Disraeli]] informs the Prince, who is so angry that he challenges Lord Randolph to a [[duel]] in the [[South of France]]. Eventually, Lord Aylesford does not attempt to seek a divorce from his wife, and Lord Blandford does not elope with Lady Aylesford. Lord Randolph sends a note of apology to the Prince, which is merely acknowledged. Disgraced, Lord Randolph and his wife leave for America.\n\nOther notable appearances include the film ''[[Young Winston]]'', in which he was portrayed by [[Robert Shaw (actor)|Robert Shaw]], and the miniseries ''[[Jennie, The Life of Lady Randolph Churchill]]'', in which he was portrayed by actor [[Ronald Pickup]], as the English aristocrat who falls in love with the daughter of an American billionaire property developer.\n\nSir Winston referred to his father's career in several of the last chapters of ''[[A History of the English-Speaking Peoples]]'' written in Winston's 'wilderness years' in the inter-war years before he was recalled to the cabinet.\n\n===Fiction===\n* The alternate history novel ''Fight and Be Right'' (by Ed Thomas), traces Churchill's further political rise in a world where his brother, the [[George Spencer-Churchill, 8th Duke of Marlborough|Marquess of Blandford]], loses the scandalous letter between the Prince of Wales and Lady Aylesford, resulting in their father, the [[John Spencer-Churchill, 7th Duke of Marlborough|Duke of Marlborough]], not being promoted to Lord Lieutenant of Ireland, and Randolph free of the scandal from the affair to rise further through the party ranks and become Prime Minister.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* [[List of Freemasons|Notable Freemasons]]\n* [[Edward the Seventh]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n==Sources==\n\n===Primary sources===\n*{{cite book |first=Lady Victoria |last=Beach |title=The Life of Sir Michael Hicks Beach |volume=2 vols |date=1932}}\n*{{cite book |first=Peregrine |last=Churchill |first2=Julian |last2=Mitchell |authorlink2=Julian Mitchell |title=Jennie: Lady Randolph Churchill |url=https://archive.org/details/jennieladyrandol00chur |url-access=registration |date=1974|publisher=New York, St. Martin's Press }}\n*{{cite book |author=[[Winston Churchill]] |title=Lord Randolph Churchill |publisher=Odhams Press |place=London |date=1905 |title-link=Lord Randolph Churchill (book)}}\n** Volume I [https://archive.org/details/lordrandolphchu01unkngoog Full text] at [[Archive.org]]\n** Volume II [https://archive.org/details/lordrandolphchu00unkngoog Full text] at Archive.org\n*{{cite book |first=Randolph S. |last=Churchill |authorlink=Randolph Churchill |title=Winston S. Churchill |volume=Youth 1874\u20131900 |place=London |date=1968 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |first=Mrs |last=Cornwallis-West |title=The Reminiscences of Lady Randolph Churchill |date=1908}}\n*{{cite book |first=Sir Henry |last=Drummond-Wolff |authorlink=Henry Drummond Wolff |title=Rambling Recollections |volume=2 vols |date=1908}}\n*{{cite book |first=Louis J. |last=Jennings |title=Speeches of Lord Randolph Churchill 1880\u201388 |volume=2 vols |date= 1889}}\n*{{cite book |first=Ralph G. |last=Martin |authorlink=Ralph G. Martin |title=Lady Randolph Churchill |volume=2 vols |origyear=1969 |date=1972}}\n*{{cite book |first= Lord | last=Rosebery |authorlink=Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery |title=Lord Randolph Churchill |url= https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.23862 |date=1906}}\n*{{cite book |first=Robin Harcourt |last=Williams |title=The Salisbury-Balfour Correspondence 1869\u20131892 |date=1899}}\n\n===Secondary sources===<!--Please do not delete this list; it has already been deleted several times before.  -->\n*{{cite book |first=Robert |last=Blake |authorlink=Robert Blake, Baron Blake |title=The Conservative Party from Peel to Thatcher |place=London |date=1985 |pages=135\u2013136, 143\u2013145, 148, 151\u2013159, 161, 193, 207}}\n*{{cite book |last=Burke |first=Bernard |last2=Burke |first2=A.P. |date=1931 |title=A Genealogical and Heraldic History of the Peerage, Baronetage, the Privy Council and Knightage |edition=89th |place=London: Burke's Peerage Ltd.}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Cokayne |first=G.E. |authorlink=George Edward Cokayne |date=1892 |title=Marlborough |journal=[[The Complete Peerage of Great Britain and Ireland extant, abeyant and dormant]] |volume=4 |place=London: George Bell & Sons; Exeter: William Pollard & Co. |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Cokayne |first=G.E. |date=1893 |title=The Complete Peerage |volume=5 |place=London: George Bell & Sons; Exeter: William Pollard & Co. |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Cokayne |first=G.E. |date=1906 |title=The Complete Baronetage |volume=5 |place=London: William Pollard & Co. |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |first=Robert Rhodes |last=James |authorlink=Robert Rhodes James |title=Lord Randolph Churchill |origyear=1959 |place=London |date=1986 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |first=Roy |last=Jenkins |authorlink=Roy Jenkins |title=The Chancellors |place=London |date=2010 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |first=Roy |last=Jenkins |title=Churchill |place=London |date=2009 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |first=Anita |last=Leslie |authorlink=Anita Leslie |title=Jennie: The Life of Lady Randolph Churchill |date=1969 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |first=Anita |last=Leslie |title=Edwardians in Love |date=1972 |ref=harv}}\n*{{EB1911|wstitle=Churchill, Lord Randolph Henry Spencer |volume=6 |pages=346\u2013347 |first=Sidney James |last=Low |authorlink=Sidney Low}}\n*{{cite journal |first=R.E. |last=Quinault |title=The Fourth Party and Conservative Opposition to Bradlaugh 1880\u20131888 |journal=[[English Historical Review]] |volume=XCI |issue=CCCLIX |pages=315\u2013340 |date=1 April 1976 |doi=10.1093/ehr/XCI.CCCLIX.315}}\n*{{cite book |first=Andrew |last=Roberts |authorlink=Andrew Roberts (historian) |title=Salisbury |place=London |date=2009 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |first=Richard |last=Shannon |authorlink=Richard Shannon (historian) |title=Gladstone: Heroic Minister 1865\u20131898 |place=London |date=1999 |pages=254\u20135, 263, 336, 366\u201372, 399, 429, 433, 444, 459, 563}}\n*{{cite journal |first=Corinne C. |last=Weston |title=Disunity on the Opposition Front Bench, 1884 |journal=[[English Historical Review]] |volume=CVI |issue=CCCCXVIII |pages=551\u2013563 |date=1 January 1991 |doi=10.1093/ehr/XCIX.CCCXCII.551}}\n\n===Archives===\n* Lord Randolph Churchill (University Library, Cambridge)\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.parliament.uk/about/living-heritage/evolutionofparliament/parliamentwork/communicating/from-the-parliamentary-collections/collections-victorian-cartoonists/merry-hercules-infant-/ Our Infant Hercules - Westminster Victorian Cartoonists - UK Parliament Living Heritage]\n\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{commons category|Lord Randolph Churchill}}\n{{wikiquote-simple}}\n{{wikisource author}}\n*{{Hansard-contribs | lord-randolph-churchill | Lord Randolph Churchill }}\n*{{Find a Grave|20133}}\n*{{UK National Archives ID}}\n*{{NPG name|name=Randolph Churchill}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = Member of Parliament for [[Woodstock (UK Parliament constituency)|Woodstock]]\n  | years  = 1874\u20131885\n  | before = [[Henry Barnett (banker)|Henry Barnett]]\n  | after  = [[Francis William Maclean]]\n}}\n{{s-new | constituency}}\n{{s-ttl\n  | title  = Member of Parliament for [[Paddington South (UK Parliament constituency)|Paddington South]]\n  | years  = 1885\u20131895\n}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[George Fardell]] }}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before= [[Henry Percy, 7th Duke of Northumberland|Earl Percy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chairman of the [[National Union of Conservative and Constitutional Associations|National Union of<br /> Conservative and Constitutional Associations]] <br /><small>(jointly with [[Michael Hicks Beach, 1st Earl St Aldwyn|Sir Michael Hicks Beach, Bt]])</small>|years=1884}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Lord Claud Hamilton (1843\u20131925)|Lord Claud Hamilton]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Secretary of State for India]]|before=[[John Wodehouse, 1st Earl of Kimberley|The Earl of Kimberley]]|after=[[John Wodehouse, 1st Earl of Kimberley|The Earl of Kimberley]]|years=1885\u20131886}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Chancellor of the Exchequer]]|before=[[William Vernon Harcourt (politician)|Sir William Harcourt]]|after=[[George Goschen, 1st Viscount Goschen|George Goschen]]|years=1886}}\n\n{{s-bef| before = [[William Ewart Gladstone|William Gladstone]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Leader of the House of Commons]]\n       | years  = 1886 }}\n{{s-aft| after  = [[William Henry Smith (1825\u20131891)|William Henry Smith]] }}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef| before = [[Michael Hicks-Beach, 1st Earl St Aldwyn|Sir Michael Hicks-Beach, Bt]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Leader of the Conservative Party (UK)|Commons Leader of the Conservatives]]\n       | years  = 1886 }}\n{{s-aft| after  = [[William Henry Smith (1825\u20131891)|William Henry Smith]] }}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{British Chancellors of the Exchequer}}\n{{Leader of the House of Commons}}\n{{First Salisbury Ministry}}\n{{UK Conservative Party}}\n{{Winston Churchill}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n*[https://www.parliament.uk/about/living-heritage/evolutionofparliament/parliamentwork/communicating/from-the-parliamentary-collections/collections-victorian-cartoonists/merry-hercules-infant-/ Randolph Churchill: Victorian Cartoons]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Churchill, Randolph}}\n[[Category:1849 births]]\n[[Category:1895 deaths]]\n[[Category:British people of English descent]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the House of Commons of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Burials at St Martin's Church, Bladon]]\n[[Category:Spencer-Churchill family|Randolph Churchill]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Conservative Party (UK)]]\n[[Category:Chancellors of the Exchequer of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British Secretaries of State]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:People educated at Cheam School]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1874\u20131880]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1880\u20131885]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1885\u20131886]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1886\u20131892]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1892\u20131895]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Merton College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Younger sons of dukes]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in England]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Freemasons of the United Grand Lodge of England]]\n[[Category:Parents of Prime Ministers of the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British politician}}\n{{about||the son of Sir Winston Churchill|Randolph Churchill|the biography|Lord Randolph Churchill (book)}}\n{{British barrelled name unused|[[Spencer-Churchill]]|Churchill}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = Lord Randolph Churchill\n|honorific-suffix =\n|image            = Lord Randolph Churchill.jpg\n|imagesize        = \n|smallimage       =\n|caption          =\n|order            = [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]]\n|term_start       = 3 August 1886\n|term_end         = 22 December 1886\n|primeminister    = [[Robert Cecil, 3rd Marquess of Salisbury|The Marquess of Salisbury]]\n|predecessor      = [[William Vernon Harcourt (politician)|William Vernon Harcourt]]\n|successor        = [[George Goschen, 1st Viscount Goschen|George Goschen]]\n|order2           = [[Leader of the House of Commons]]\n|term_start2      = 3 August 1886\n|term_end2        = 14 January 1887\n|primeminister2   = [[Robert Cecil, 3rd Marquess of Salisbury|The Marquess of Salisbury]]\n|predecessor2     = [[William Ewart Gladstone]]\n|successor2       = [[William Henry Smith (1825\u20131891)|William Henry Smith]]\n|office3          = [[Secretary of State for India]]\n|term_start3      = 24 June 1885\n|term_end3        = 28 January 1886\n|primeminister3   = [[Robert Cecil, 3rd Marquess of Salisbury|The Marquess of Salisbury]]\n|preceded3        = [[John Wodehouse, 1st Earl of Kimberley|The Earl of Kimberley]]\n|succeeded3       = [[John Wodehouse, 1st Earl of Kimberley|The Earl of Kimberley]]\n|birth_name       = Randolph Henry Spencer-Churchill\n|birth_date       = 13 February 1849\n|birth_place      = [[Belgravia]], [[London]], England\n|death_date       = {{death date and age|1895|1|24|1849|2|13|df=yes}}\n|death_place      = [[Westminster]], London, England\n|party            = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|spouse           = {{marriage|[[Lady Randolph Churchill|Jennie Jerome]]|15 April 1874}}\n|children         = [[Winston Churchill|Sir Winston Spencer-Churchill]]<br/>[[John Strange Spencer-Churchill|John Spencer-Churchill]]\n|parents          = [[John Spencer-Churchill, 7th Duke of Marlborough]]<br/>[[Frances Anne Spencer-Churchill, Duchess of Marlborough|Lady Frances Anne Vane]]\n|profession       = Politician\n|alma_mater       = [[Merton College, Oxford]]\n}}\n\n'''Lord Randolph Henry Spencer-Churchill''' (13 February 1849 \u2013 24 January 1895) was a British statesman.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Lord-Randolph-Churchill-British-politician |title=Lord Randolph Churchill {{!}} British politician |website=Encyclopedia Britannica |language=en |access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref> Churchill was a [[Tory]] radical and coined the term '[[One-nation conservatism|Tory democracy]]'.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Quinault |first=R.E. |date=March 1979 |title=Lord Randolph Churchill and Tory Democracy, 1880\u20131885 |url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/historical-journal/article/lord-randolph-churchill-and-tory-democracy-18801885/E2FA5614DFCC64D5E6F77DDC8F926720 |journal=The Historical Journal |language=en |volume=22 |issue=1 |pages=141\u2013165 |doi=10.1017/S0018246X0001671X |issn=0018-246X}}</ref> He inspired a generation of party managers, created the National Union of the Conservative Party, and broke new ground in modern budgetary presentations, attracting admiration and criticism from across the political spectrum. His most acerbic critics were in his own party, among his closest friends; but his disloyalty to [[Lord Salisbury]] was the beginning of the end of what should have been a glittering career.  His elder son, [[Winston Churchill|Winston]], wrote a biography of him in 1906.<ref>Churchill, Winston C. 1906. ''Lord Randolph Churchill''. 2 vols, Macmillan, London.</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Lord Randolph Churchill by Hills and Saunders, 1860s.jpg|150px|thumb|left|Churchill in the 1860s]]\nBorn at 3 [[Wilton Terrace]], [[Belgravia]], London, Randolph Spencer was the third son of [[John Spencer-Churchill, 7th Duke of Marlborough|John Spencer-Churchill, Marquess of Blandford]], and his wife the Marchioness of Blandford (''[[n\u00e9e]]'' [[Frances Anne Spencer-Churchill, Duchess of Marlborough|Lady Frances Vane]]); upon John's father's death in 1857, they became the (7th) Duke of Marlborough, and the Duchess of Marlborough, respectively.<ref name=\"ODNB\">{{cite ODNB|id=5404|title=Churchill, Lord Randolph Henry Spencer|first=Roland|last=Quinault}}</ref> As the younger son of a Marquess, Randolph had a [[Courtesy titles in the United Kingdom|courtesy title]], and was ''Lord Randolph Churchill''; but was a commoner able to sit in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]].\n\nChurchill attended [[Cheam School|Tabor's Preparatory School, Cheam]], then in 1863 [[Eton College]], where he remained until 1865.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/> He did not stand out either at academic work or sport while at Eton; his contemporaries describe him as a vivacious and rather unruly boy.{{sfn|Low|1911|p=346}} Among the lifelong friendships he made at school were with [[Arthur Balfour]] and [[Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery|Archibald Primrose]] (later Lord Rosebery).<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>  \n\nIn October 1867, Churchill matriculated at [[Merton College, Oxford]]. At Oxford, Primrose \u2013 now with his own courtesy title of ''Lord Dalmeny'' \u2013 was along with Churchill a member of the [[Bullingdon Club]], and joined him at the Club's champagne-fuelled parties.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">[[Frank Harris]], ''[[My Life and Loves]]'', 1922\u201327; p. 483</ref> Randolph was frequently in trouble with the university authorities for drunkenness, smoking in academic dress, and smashing windows at the [[Randolph Hotel, Oxford|Randolph Hotel]]. His rowdy behaviour was infectious, rubbing off on friends and contemporaries; he gained a reputation as an ''[[enfant terrible]]''.<ref>[[Leo McKinstry]], ''Rosebery: Statesman in Turmoil'', pp. 23, 33</ref> He had a liking for hunting, but was also a well-read historian. He gaining a second-class degree in [[jurisprudence]] and modern history in 1870.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/> \n\nChurchill experienced none of the early doubts but made many mistakes, as alluded to in Rosebery's biography.<ref>Rosebery, Ld Randolph, (1906);[[Leo McKinstry]], ''Rosebery: Statesman in Turmoil'', p. 58</ref> He never regretted being an early friend and admirer of the Disraelis. His behaviour was, however, the later cause of dissension in his relations with a colder, more aloof, disciplinarian [[Lord Salisbury|Salisbury]]. In 1871 Churchill and his elder brother [[George Spencer-Churchill, 8th Duke of Marlborough|George]] were initiated into the rites of [[Freemasonry]], as later his son Winston would be.<ref>{{cite web |last=Churchill |first=Randolph |title=Masonic Papers |url=http://www.freemasons-freemasonry.com/freemasonry_england.html |work=The Development of the Craft in England |publisher=freemasons-freemasonary.com |accessdate=30 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nAt the general election of 1874 Churchill was elected to Parliament as [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] member for [[Woodstock (UK Parliament constituency)|Woodstock]], near the family seat, defeating [[George Charles Brodrick|George Brodrick]], a Fellow of Merton. His [[maiden speech]], delivered in his first session, prompted compliments from [[William Vernon Harcourt (politician)|William Harcourt]] and [[Benjamin Disraeli]], who wrote to the Queen of Churchill's \"energy and natural flow\".<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>\n\nChurchill was a close friend of [[Nathan Rothschild, 1st Baron Rothschild]], and received \"extensive loans\" from the Rothschilds. He reported on the mining industry in South Africa on their behalf, where their agent [[Cecil Rhodes]] was consolidating mining deposits which ultimately led to the creation of [[De Beers]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rothschildarchive.org/business/rothschild_clients |title=The Rothschild Archive |website=rothschildarchive.org |accessdate=24 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Marriage and medical condition==\n[[File:Lord Randolph Churchill and Lady Jennie Jerome (1874) (A).jpg|thumb|right|upright=|Lord Randolph Churchill and [[Lady Randolph Churchill]] (Jennie Jerome) in [[Paris]] (1874) by [[Georges Penabert]]]]\n\nLord Randolph Churchill was married at the [[Embassy of the United Kingdom, Paris|British Embassy in Paris]] on 15 April 1874 to [[Lady Randolph Churchill|Jennie Jerome]], daughter of [[Leonard Jerome]], an American businessman.<ref>Anita Leslie. ''Jennie: The Life of Lady Randolph Churchill'', 1969</ref> The couple had two sons:\n*[[Winston Churchill|Winston Leonard Spencer-Churchill]] (30 November 1874{{snd}}24 January 1965)\n*[[Jack Churchill (1880\u20131947)|John Strange \"Jack\" Spencer-Churchill]] (4 February 1880{{snd}}23 February 1947)\n\nIn January 1875, about a month after Winston's birth, Randolph made repeated visits to Dr [[Oscar Clayton]].<ref name=\"Morgan\">Ted Morgan, ''Churchill: Young Man in a Hurry, 1874\u20131915'' (1984), p. 23</ref> He had twenty years to live, but suffered from debilitating illness, particularly in his last decade. Quinault writing in the ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'' considers that he probably was passing through the stages of [[secondary syphilis]] and then [[tertiary syphilis]], but mentions a [[brain tumour]] and [[multiple sclerosis]] as other possible causes.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/> It is definitely the case that he was treated for [[syphilis]], and it has been suggested that he was suffering from symptoms of the [[mercury (element)|mercury]]-based medication.<ref name=\"Foster\">{{cite book |first=R. F. |last=Foster |title=Lord Randolph Churchill: A Political Life |authorlink=R. F. Foster (historian) |page=218 |date=1988}}</ref> Clayton was a society doctor and specialist in the treatment of syphilis at his London practice at 5,{{nbsp}}[[Harley Street]].<ref name=\"Morgan\"/> [[Robson Roose]], who was the Churchills' family doctor in the 1880s, had written on syphilis, his diagnosis, as a root cause of debilitating disease. He referred Randolph to the specialist [[Thomas Buzzard]], but continued to prescribe [[potassium iodide]] and mercury.<ref name=\"Foster\"/>\n\nAccording to [[Frank Harris]], who published the allegation in his scandalous autobiography, ''[[My Life and Loves]]'' (1922\u201327), \"Randolph had caught syphilis...\" <ref name=\"Morgan\"/> He relied on a story by [[Louis Jennings]], an associate of Randolph's who had later fallen out with him. John H. Mather of the [[National Churchill Library and Center]] called into question Harris' veracity and offered the alternative theory of a \"left side brain tumour\". Mather noted that \"There is no indication that Lady Randolph or her sons were infected with syphilis.\"<ref name=\"maladiesetmort\">{{cite news|url=http://www.winstonchurchill.org/resources/myths/144-lord-randolph-churchill-maladies-et-mort|title=Lord Randolph Churchill: Maladies et Mort|accessdate=17 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===The \"Fourth Party\"===\n[[File:The Fourth Party Vanity Fair 1 December 1880.jpg|thumb|left|<center>\"The Fourth Party\" Spencer-Churchill, Balfour, Drummond-Wolff and Gorst as caricatured by Spy ([[Leslie Ward]]) in ''[[Vanity Fair (British magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', 1 December 1880</center>]]\nIt was not until 1878 that he came to public notice as the exponent of independent Conservatism. He made a series of furious attacks on [[Sir Stafford Northcote]], [[Richard Assheton Cross, 1st Viscount Cross|R. A. Cross]], and other prominent members of the \"old gang\". [[George Sclater-Booth, 1st Baron Basing|George Sclater-Booth]] (afterwards 1st Baron Basing), [[President of the Local Government Board]], was a specific target, and the minister's County Government Bill was fiercely denounced as the \"crowning dishonour to Tory principles\", and the \"supreme violation of political honesty\".{{sfn|Low|1911|p=346}} Lord Randolph's attitude, and the vituperative fluency of his invective, made him a parliamentary figure of some importance before the dissolution of the 1874 parliament, though he was not yet taken quite seriously, owing to his high-pitched hysterical laugh.<ref>Blake, pp. 134-35</ref>\n\nIn the new parliament of 1880 he speedily began to play a more notable role. Along with [[Henry Drummond Wolff]], [[John Eldon Gorst|John Gorst]] and occasionally [[Arthur Balfour]], he made himself known as the audacious opponent of the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] administration and the unsparing critic of the Conservative front bench. The \"fourth party\", as it was nicknamed, at first did little damage to the government, but awakened the opposition from its apathy; Churchill roused the Conservatives by leading resistance to [[Charles Bradlaugh]], the member for [[Northampton (UK Parliament constituency)|Northampton]], who, an avowed atheist or agnostic, was prepared to take the parliamentary oath under protest. Stafford Northcote, the Conservative leader in the Lower House, was forced to take a strong line on this difficult question by the energy of the fourth party.{{sfn|Low|1911|p=346}}\n\nThe long controversy over Bradlaugh's seat showed that Lord Randolph Churchill was a parliamentary champion who added to his audacity much tactical skill and shrewdness. He continued to play a conspicuous part throughout the parliament of 1880\u201385, targeting [[William Ewart Gladstone]] as well as the Conservative front bench, some of whose members, particularly [[R. A. Cross, 1st Viscount Cross|Sir Richard Cross]] and [[William Henry Smith (1825\u20131891)|William Henry Smith]], he singled out for attack when they opposed the reduced Army estimates.{{sfn|Low|1911|p=346}} This would be the ostensible cause for his resignation because Salisbury failed to support his Chancellor in cabinet. They opposed his unionist politics of 'economising' by Tory tradition, making Randolph grow to hate cabinet meetings.<ref>W S Churchill, ''Life of Lord Randolph Churchill'', 2 vols, chap XIV<!-- publisher, ISSN/ISBN, page(s) needed --></ref>\n\nFrom the beginning of the [[History of Modern Egypt|Egyptian]] imbroglio Lord Randolph was emphatically opposed to almost every step taken by the government. He declared that the suppression of [[\u2018Urabi Revolt|Urabi Pasha's rebellion]] was an error, and the restoration of the [[khedive]]'s authority a crime. He called Gladstone the \"[[Moloch]] of [[Midlothian (UK Parliament constituency) (1708\u20131918)|Midlothian]]\", for whom torrents of blood had been shed in Africa. He was equally severe on the domestic policy of the administration, and was particularly bitter in his criticism of the [[Kilmainham Treaty]] and the rapprochement between the Gladstonians and the [[Charles Stewart Parnell|Parnellites]].{{sfn|Low|1911|p=346}}\n\n===Tory Democracy===\n[[File:Randolph Churchill.jpg|200px|right|thumb|Lord Randolph Churchill]]\nBy 1885 he had formulated the policy of progressive Conservatism which was known as \"[[Tory Democracy]]\". He declared that the Conservatives ought to adopt, rather than oppose, popular reforms, and to challenge the claims of the Liberals to pose as champions of the masses. His views were largely accepted by the official Conservative leaders in the treatment of the Gladstonian [[Representation of the People Act 1884]]. Lord Randolph insisted that the principle of the bill should be accepted by the opposition, and that resistance should be focused on the refusal of the government to combine with it a scheme of redistribution. The prominent, and on the whole judicious and successful, part he played in the debates on these questions, still further increased his influence with the rank and file of the Conservatives in the constituencies.{{sfn|Low|1911|p=346}}\n\nAt the same time he was actively spreading his gospel of democratic Toryism in a series of platform campaigns. In 1883 and 1884 he went to the radical stronghold of [[Birmingham]], and in the latter year took part in a Conservative garden party at Aston Manor, at which his opponents paid him the compliment of raising a serious riot. He gave constant attention to the party organisation, which had fallen into considerable disorder after 1880, and was an active promoter of the [[Primrose League]], which owed its origin to the inspiration of one of his own \u201cfourth party\u201d colleagues.{{sfn|Low|1911|p=346}}\n\n===Central Office and National Union===\nIn 1884 progressive Toryism won out. At the conference of the [[National Union of Conservative Associations]], Lord Randolph was nominated chairman, despite the opposition of the parliamentary leaders.  A split was averted by Lord Randolph's voluntary resignation which he had done his best to engineer; but the episode had confirmed his title to a leading place in the Tory ranks.{{sfn|Low|1911|p=346}}<ref>Blake, p. 145</ref>\n\nHe built up Tory Democracy in the towns reinforcing the urban middle classes part in the party, while simultaneously including a working-class element.  His unsuccessful bid for the party leadership was inextricably part of the National Union's attempt to control the party organization.<ref>Blake, p. 152</ref> It had originally been founded by Tory peers to organize propaganda to attract working men's votes, registration, choose candidates, conduct elections; associations were linked to provincial unions. Lord Randolph was not the originator but his campaign of 1884 encouraged the leadership to improve on their designs. For the first time since 1832 the Conservatives won in the majority of English boroughs in November 1885.<ref>R.R. James; Blake, pp. 152-53</ref>\n\nIt was strengthened by the prominent part he played in the events immediately preceding the fall of the Liberal government in 1885; and when [[Hugh Childers]]'s budget resolutions were defeated by the Conservatives, aided by about half the Parnellites, Lord Randolph Churchill's admirers were justified in proclaiming him to have been the \"organiser of victory\".{{sfn|Low|1911|p=346}}\n\n===Secretary of State for India===\nIn Lord Salisbury's \"caretaker\" cabinet of 1885, Churchill was appointed [[Secretary of State for India]], assuming office on 24{{nbsp}}June 1885.<ref name=DIB>[[s:Dictionary of Indian Biography/Churchill, Lord Randolph Henry Spencer]]</ref> As the price of entry he demanded that Sir Stafford Northcote be removed from the Commons, despite being the Conservative leader there. Salisbury was more than willing to concede this, and Northcote went to the Lords as the Earl of Iddlesleigh.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\nDespite entering office with a reputation for progressive views on India, Churchill 's tenure was, in the words of the historian and biographer R.F. Foster, 'traditionally reactionary'.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Foster |first1=R.F. |title=Lord Randolph Churchill: A Political Life |date=1981 |publisher=Oxford University Press |page=168}}</ref> He enthusiastically supported a free trade policy which favoured British imports over Indian goods. He increased spending on the Indian Army at the expense of public works such as railways, roads and irrigation, which were all sharply reduced under his secretaryship, while also re-directing money which had been set aside for future famine relief.<ref>Foster, ''Randolph Churchill'', pp. 189-190, 193-194</ref> His attitude towards the native Indians was similarly illiberal. He refused to allow reforms which would have increased Indian representation within the civil service and army, and, in a public speech at Birmingham, he famously described a deputation to Britain by three Indian politicians, led by [[N. G. Chandavarkar]], as the 'three Bengalee baboos'.<ref>Foster, ''Randolph Churchill'', pp. 193, 204-205</ref> \n\nHowever, Churchill's most famous act during his tenure at the India Office was the invasion and annexation of Burma in the [[Third Anglo-Burmese War]]. Siding with British commercial (especially cotton) and military interests, and hoping to boost Conservative fortunes in the upcoming general election, Churchill directed the [[Viceroy]], [[Frederick Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 1st Marquess of Dufferin and Ava|Lord Dufferin]], to invade [[Upper Burma]] in November 1885.<ref>Foster, ''Randolph Churchill'', pp. 206-213</ref> With little discussion, Churchill then decided to annex the final remnant of the once great Burmese kingdom, adding it as a new province of the Indian [[British Raj|Raj]] as a \"New Year present\" for [[Queen Victoria]] on New Year's Day 1886. Not only is the war itself widely regarded as an unnecessary piece of blatant [[imperialism]], but the continuing guerrilla war lasted into the later 1880s and cost the Indian taxpayer ten times Churchill's original estimates.<ref>Foster, ''Randolph Churchill'', p. 209</ref> <ref>Kwarsi Kwarteng, ''Ghosts of Empire: Britain's Legacies in the Modern World'', Bloomsbury, 2011, Part III</ref>\n\nIn the autumn election of 1885 he contested [[Birmingham Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Birmingham Central]] against [[John Bright]], and though defeated here, was at the same time returned by a very large majority for [[Paddington South (UK Parliament constituency)|South Paddington]].{{sfn|Low|1911|p=346}}\n\nIn the contest which arose over [[William Ewart Gladstone]]'s [[First Irish Home Rule Bill|Home Rule]] bill, Lord Randolph again bore a conspicuous part, and in the electioneering campaign his activity was only second to that of some of the [[Liberal Unionist Party|Liberal Unionists]], [[Spencer Cavendish, 8th Duke of Devonshire|Lord Hartington]], [[George Joachim Goschen, 1st Viscount Goschen|George Goschen]] and [[Joseph Chamberlain]]. He was now the recognised Conservative champion in the Lower Chamber, and when the second Salisbury administration was formed after the general election of 1886 he became [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] and [[Leader of the House of Commons]].{{sfn|Low|1911|p=346}}\n\n===End of political career===\n[[File:Edward Linley Sambourne - Lord Randolph Churchill, 1881.png|thumb|upright|1881 [[Punch (magazine)|''Punch'']] cartoon by [[Edward Linley Sambourne]] of Lord Randolph Churchill, M.P., as a \"midge with no sting in Parliament.\"]]\n\nChurchill was new to the leadership ranks, and became a relatively isolated figure in the cabinet. He did not think in terms of consulting his supporters and building a base in Commons; instead, he decided to use his strong public support to impose his positions on Prime Minister Lord Salisbury in both domestic and foreign affairs. He decided to demonstrate to the public that the Conservatives could be as economical in budgetary matters as Gladstone had been. Therefore, he proposed a budget with significant slashes that surprised and annoyed the Conservative MPs. They were willing to compromise, but he insisted on additional cuts in the Army and Navy that alarmed the service ministers. Churchill decided to threaten resignation\u2014it proved one of the great blunders in British political history. In his resignation letter he stated that it was because he was unable as Chancellor to support the service. He expected his resignation to be followed by the unconditional surrender of the cabinet, and his restoration to office on his own terms. Instead, Salisbury accepted the resignation, and Churchill was out in the cold. Goschen replaced him as Chancellor.<ref>Norman McCord and Bill Purdue, ''British History, 1815-1914'' (2nd ed. 2007) pp 410-11,.</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=Eric Alexander |title=Chief Whip |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NP7lDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT88 |year=1961 |pages=86\u201389 |isbn=9781442654655}}</ref> For the next few years there was some speculation about a return to front-line politics, but Churchill's own career was over.{{sfn|Low|1911|p=347}} Even so, his economising ideas survived yet in the \"Dartford Programme\" of September 1886.\n\nAlthough Lord Randolph continued to sit in Parliament, his health was in serious decline throughout the 1890s. He was an ardent patron of horse-racing and in 1889, his horse [[L'Abbesse de Jouarre]] won [[Epsom Oaks|The Oaks]]. In 1891 he went to South Africa, in search both of health and relaxation. He travelled for some months through [[Cape Colony]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.matjiesfontein.com/About/index.htm |title=Matjiesfontein History - Matjiesfontein |website=matjiesfontein.com |accessdate=24 July 2017}}</ref> the [[South African Republic|Transvaal]] and [[Rhodesia]], making notes on the politics and economics of the countries, shooting lions, and recording his impressions in letters to a London newspaper, which were afterwards republished under the title of ''Men, Mines and Animals in South Africa''. He attacked [[William Ewart Gladstone|Gladstone]]'s [[Second Irish Home Rule Bill|Second Home Rule Bill]] with energy,{{sfn|Low|1911|p=347}} and gave fiery pro-Union speeches in Ireland.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} During this time he coined the phrase \"Ulster will fight, and Ulster will be right\", echoing his earlier remark that in opposing Irish Home Rule \"the Orange card would be the one to play\".<ref>{{cite book |author=Paul Bew |title=Churchill and Ireland |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UzrcCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT55 |year=2016 |publisher=Oxford University Press |pages=55\u201356 |isbn=9780191071492}}</ref>\n\nIt was soon apparent that Churchill's powers had been undermined by the illness which was to take his life at the age of 45. As the session of 1893 wore on, his speeches lost their old effectiveness. His last speech in the House was delivered in the debate on the East African Scheme in June 1894, and was a painful failure.{{sfn|Low|1911|p=347}}\n\n==Death==\nAn attempted round-the-world journey failed to cure Lord Randolph of his debilitating illness. He started in the autumn of 1894, accompanied by his wife, but his health soon became so feeble that he was brought back hurriedly from Cairo. He reached England shortly before Christmas, and died in [[Westminster]].{{sfn|Low|1911|p=347}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=cnS1ua%2FEVI2BXjrLIgIY7Q&scan=1 |title=Index entry |access-date=24 April 2018 |work=[[FreeBMD]] |publisher=ONS}}</ref> The gross value of his personal estate was entered in the Probate Registry at \u00a375,971.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9C01E5DF133DE433A25756C0A9659C94649ED7CF |title=RANDOLPH CHURCHILL'S WILL; Details of the Estate Bequeathed to His Wife and Children |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=5 March 1895 |page=5 |access-date=25 July 2019 |publisher=[[The New York Times Company]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090222031341/http://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9C01E5DF133DE433A25756C0A9659C94649ED7CF |archive-date=22 February 2009}}</ref> This is the financial equivalent of over \u00a38.34 million in 2018 terms, using the retail price index.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.measuringworth.com/ppoweruk/result.php?use%5B%5D=CPI&use%5B%5D=NOMINALEARN&year_early=1894&pound71=76&shilling71=&pence71=&amount=76&year_source=1894&year_result=2010r |work=Measuring Worth \u2013 Measures of worth, inflation rates, saving calculator, relative value, worth of a dollar, worth of a pound, purchasing power, gold prices, GDP... |access-date=16 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610220910/http://www.measuringworth.com/ppoweruk/result.php?use%5B%5D=CPI&use%5B%5D=NOMINALEARN&year_early=1894&pound71=76&shilling71=&pence71=&amount=76&year_source=1894&year_result=2010r |archive-date=10 June 2015 |title=Purchasing Power of British Pounds from 1245 to Present |first=Lawrence H. |last=Officer |first2=Samuel H. |last2=Williamson |year=2012}}</ref> He is buried near his wife and sons at [[St Martin's Church, Bladon]], near [[Woodstock, Oxfordshire]].\n\nHis widow, Lady Randolph Churchill, married [[George Cornwallis-West]] in 1900, when she became known as Mrs. George Cornwallis-West.  After that marriage was dissolved, she resumed by [[deed poll]] her prior married name, Lady Randolph Churchill. (Lord Randolph was her husband's courtesy title as the younger son of a duke and in English law does not qualify as a noble title in its own right.) Lord Randolph's son, Sir [[Winston Churchill]], died on 24 January 1965, aged 90, exactly 70 years after the death of his father, having lived twice as long.\n\n==Personality and reputation==\nRosebery described his old friend and political opponent, after his death, thus: \"his nervous system was always tense and highly strung; ...he seems to have had no knowledge  of men, no consideration of their feelings, no give and take.\"  But he continued, \"in congenial society, his conversation was wholly delightful. He would then display his mastery of pleasant irony and banter; for with those playthings he was at his best.\"<ref>Gertrude Atherton, ''Review: Lord Randolph Churchill'', Reviewed Work: Lord Randolph Churchill by Lord Rosebery, The North American Review Vol. 184, No. 606 (Jan. 4, 1907), pp. 87\u201391, at p. 90. (5 pages) Published by: University of Northern Iowa {{jstor|25105753}}</ref>\n\nBiographer [[Roy Jenkins]], pointing to his brash and slightly vulgar charisma, asked, \"Was he ever near to being a serious statesman?\":\n\n<blockquote>Undoubtedly, he had some high political talents. He had a gift for mordant, wounding, sometimes very funny phrases. And, having thought up the most outrageous attack he had the nerve to deliver it, without fear of offending taste or friends or damaging his own repute....He was strong on insolence. He also had other attributes necessary to make his words resound, and his fame increase: a mnemonic name, an  idiosyncratic appearance, and good delivery, whether on the platform or in the House of Commons. In addition he had sporadic charm, although intermingled with offensive and often pointless rudeness.<ref>Roy Jenkins, ''The Chancellors'' (1998), pp. 11-12.</ref></blockquote>\n\nJenkins compares his youth to that of [[William Pitt the Younger]]: \"Pitt was Prime Minister for 19 of his 46 years. Churchill had 11 months in office and was without rival in attracting so much attention and achieving so little.\"<ref>Jenkins, ''The Chancellors'' (1998) p. 36.</ref>\n\n==Family==\n;Parents\n*[[John Spencer-Churchill, 7th Duke of Marlborough]]\n*[[Frances Anne Spencer-Churchill, Duchess of Marlborough|Lady Frances Anne Emily Vane]] (15 April 1822{{snd}}16 April 1899), the eldest daughter of the [[Charles William Vane, 3rd Marquess of Londonderry|3rd Marquess of Londonderry]] and Lady [[Frances Anne Vane, Marchioness of Londonderry|Frances Anne Emily Vane-Tempest]].\n;Siblings\n*[[George Spencer-Churchill, 8th Duke of Marlborough|George Charles Spencer-Churchill, 8th Duke of Marlborough]] (13 May 1844{{snd}}9 November 1892)\n*Lord Frederick John Winston Spencer-Churchill (2 February 1846{{snd}}5 August 1850)\n*[[Lady Cornelia Henrietta Maria Spencer-Churchill]] (17 September 1847{{snd}}[[Mayfair|Upper Brook Street, Mayfair, London]], 22 January 1927), married 25 May 1868 [[Ivor Bertie Guest, 1st Baron Wimborne]], by whom she had issue.\n*[[Lady Rosamund Jane Frances Spencer-Churchill]] (1851\u2013 3 December 1920), married 12 July 1877 [[William Fellowes, 2nd Baron de Ramsey]], by whom she had issue\n*[[Lady Fanny Octavia Louise Spencer-Churchill]] (29 January 1853{{snd}}5 August 1904), married 9 June 1873 [[Edward Marjoribanks, 2nd Baron Tweedmouth]], by whom she had issue.\n*[[Anne Innes-Ker, Duchess of Roxburghe|Lady Anne Emily Spencer-Churchill]] ([[Mayfair|Lower Brook Street, Mayfair, London]], 14 November 1854{{snd}}[[Mayfair|South Audley Street, Mayfair, London]], 20 June 1923), married 11 June 1874 [[James Innes-Ker, 7th Duke of Roxburghe]], by whom she had issue.\n*Lord Charles Ashley Spencer-Churchill (1856{{snd}}11 March 1858)\n*Lord Augustus Robert Spencer-Churchill (4 July 1858{{snd}}12 May 1859)\n*[[Lady Georgiana Elizabeth Spencer-Churchill]] (10 [[St James's Square]], St James's, London, 14 May 1860{{snd}}9 February 1906), married 4 June 1883 [[Richard Curzon, 4th Earl Howe|Richard George Penn Curzon, 4th Earl Howe]], by whom she had issue.\n*[[Lady Sarah Wilson|Lady Sarah Isabella Augusta Spencer-Churchill]] (1865{{snd}}22 October 1929), a war correspondent during the [[Boer War]]; married 21 November 1891 Lt. Col. Gordon Chesney Wilson (son of Sir Samuel Wilson, MP)\n;Spouse\n*[[Lady Randolph Churchill|Jennie Jerome]]\n;Children\n*[[Winston Churchill|Sir Winston Churchill]]\n*[[Jack Churchill (1880\u20131947)|John Strange Spencer-Churchill]]\n\n==Film, television and literary depictions==\nIn the ITV historical drama series ''[[Edward the Seventh]]'', Lord Randolph (played by [[Derek Fowlds]]) is featured as a more natural character, sociably similar to [[Edward VII of the United Kingdom|Albert Edward, Prince of Wales]] and his other friends. His downfall is represented when he confronts [[Alexandra of Denmark|Alexandra, Princess of Wales]] and demands she use her influence with the Prince to stop [[Lord Aylesford]] proceeding with a divorce from his wife, Lady Aylesford, after she had planned to elope with Lord Randolph's elder brother, the [[George Spencer-Churchill, 8th Duke of Marlborough|Marquess of Blandford]]. He threatens to expose letters from the Prince to Lady Aylesford, so scandalous, so he says, that if they were to be exposed, \"the Prince of Wales would never sit on the throne of England.\"\n\nOutraged, the Princess goes to see the [[Queen Victoria|Queen]], who is equally indignant. Prime Minister [[Benjamin Disraeli, 1st Earl of Beaconsfield|Benjamin Disraeli]] informs the Prince, who is so angry that he challenges Lord Randolph to a [[duel]] in the [[South of France]]. Eventually, Lord Aylesford does not attempt to seek a divorce from his wife, and Lord Blandford does not elope with Lady Aylesford. Lord Randolph sends a note of apology to the Prince, which is merely acknowledged. Disgraced, Lord Randolph and his wife leave for America.\n\nOther notable appearances include the film ''[[Young Winston]]'', in which he was portrayed by [[Robert Shaw (actor)|Robert Shaw]], and the miniseries ''[[Jennie, The Life of Lady Randolph Churchill]]'', in which he was portrayed by actor [[Ronald Pickup]], as the English aristocrat who falls in love with the daughter of an American billionaire property developer.\n\nSir Winston referred to his father's career in several of the last chapters of ''[[A History of the English-Speaking Peoples]]'' written in Winston's 'wilderness years' in the inter-war years before he was recalled to the cabinet.\n\n===Fiction===\n* The alternate history novel ''Fight and Be Right'' (by Ed Thomas), traces Churchill's further political rise in a world where his brother, the [[George Spencer-Churchill, 8th Duke of Marlborough|Marquess of Blandford]], loses the scandalous letter between the Prince of Wales and Lady Aylesford, resulting in their father, the [[John Spencer-Churchill, 7th Duke of Marlborough|Duke of Marlborough]], not being promoted to Lord Lieutenant of Ireland, and Randolph free of the scandal from the affair to rise further through the party ranks and become Prime Minister.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* [[List of Freemasons|Notable Freemasons]]\n* [[Edward the Seventh]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n==Sources==\n\n===Primary sources===\n*{{cite book |first=Lady Victoria |last=Beach |title=The Life of Sir Michael Hicks Beach |volume=2 vols |date=1932}}\n*{{cite book |first=Peregrine |last=Churchill |first2=Julian |last2=Mitchell |authorlink2=Julian Mitchell |title=Jennie: Lady Randolph Churchill |url=https://archive.org/details/jennieladyrandol00chur |url-access=registration |date=1974|publisher=New York, St. Martin's Press }}\n*{{cite book |author=[[Winston Churchill]] |title=Lord Randolph Churchill |publisher=Odhams Press |place=London |date=1905 |title-link=Lord Randolph Churchill (book)}}\n** Volume I [https://archive.org/details/lordrandolphchu01unkngoog Full text] at [[Archive.org]]\n** Volume II [https://archive.org/details/lordrandolphchu00unkngoog Full text] at Archive.org\n*{{cite book |first=Randolph S. |last=Churchill |authorlink=Randolph Churchill |title=Winston S. Churchill |volume=Youth 1874\u20131900 |place=London |date=1968 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |first=Mrs |last=Cornwallis-West |title=The Reminiscences of Lady Randolph Churchill |date=1908}}\n*{{cite book |first=Sir Henry |last=Drummond-Wolff |authorlink=Henry Drummond Wolff |title=Rambling Recollections |volume=2 vols |date=1908}}\n*{{cite book |first=Louis J. |last=Jennings |title=Speeches of Lord Randolph Churchill 1880\u201388 |volume=2 vols |date= 1889}}\n*{{cite book |first=Ralph G. |last=Martin |authorlink=Ralph G. Martin |title=Lady Randolph Churchill |volume=2 vols |origyear=1969 |date=1972}}\n*{{cite book |first= Lord | last=Rosebery |authorlink=Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery |title=Lord Randolph Churchill |url= https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.23862 |date=1906}}\n*{{cite book |first=Robin Harcourt |last=Williams |title=The Salisbury-Balfour Correspondence 1869\u20131892 |date=1899}}\n\n===Secondary sources===<!--Please do not delete this list; it has already been deleted several times before.  -->\n*{{cite book |first=Robert |last=Blake |authorlink=Robert Blake, Baron Blake |title=The Conservative Party from Peel to Thatcher |place=London |date=1985 |pages=135\u2013136, 143\u2013145, 148, 151\u2013159, 161, 193, 207}}\n*{{cite book |last=Burke |first=Bernard |last2=Burke |first2=A.P. |date=1931 |title=A Genealogical and Heraldic History of the Peerage, Baronetage, the Privy Council and Knightage |edition=89th |place=London: Burke's Peerage Ltd.}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Cokayne |first=G.E. |authorlink=George Edward Cokayne |date=1892 |title=Marlborough |journal=[[The Complete Peerage of Great Britain and Ireland extant, abeyant and dormant]] |volume=4 |place=London: George Bell & Sons; Exeter: William Pollard & Co. |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Cokayne |first=G.E. |date=1893 |title=The Complete Peerage |volume=5 |place=London: George Bell & Sons; Exeter: William Pollard & Co. |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Cokayne |first=G.E. |date=1906 |title=The Complete Baronetage |volume=5 |place=London: William Pollard & Co. |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |first=Robert Rhodes |last=James |authorlink=Robert Rhodes James |title=Lord Randolph Churchill |origyear=1959 |place=London |date=1986 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |first=Roy |last=Jenkins |authorlink=Roy Jenkins |title=The Chancellors |place=London |date=2010 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |first=Roy |last=Jenkins |title=Churchill |place=London |date=2009 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |first=Anita |last=Leslie |authorlink=Anita Leslie |title=Jennie: The Life of Lady Randolph Churchill |date=1969 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |first=Anita |last=Leslie |title=Edwardians in Love |date=1972 |ref=harv}}\n*{{EB1911|wstitle=Churchill, Lord Randolph Henry Spencer |volume=6 |pages=346\u2013347 |first=Sidney James |last=Low |authorlink=Sidney Low}}\n*{{cite 