{"title_page": "Dras River", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox river\n| name               = Dras River\n| name_native        = \n| name_native_lang   = \n| name_other         = \n| name_etymology     = \n<!---------------------- IMAGE & MAP -->\n| image              = Drasvalley.JPG\n| image_size         = 290 px\n| image_caption      = Dras River\n| map                = \n| map_size           = \n| map_caption        = \n| pushpin_map        = India Ladakh\n| pushpin_map_size   = \n| pushpin_map_caption= The confluence of the Dras River with the Suru River\n<!---------------------- LOCATION -->\n| subdivision_type1  = Country\n| subdivision_name1  = [[India]]\n| subdivision_type2  = Union territory\n| subdivision_name2  = [[Ladakh]]\n| subdivision_type3  = District\n| subdivision_name3  = [[Kargil district|Kargil]]\n<!---------------------- PHYSICAL CHARACTERISTICS -->\n| length             = {{convert|86|km|mi|abbr=on}} \n| width_min          = \n| width_avg          = \n| width_max          = \n| depth_min          = \n| depth_avg          = \n| depth_max          = \n| discharge1_location= \n| discharge1_min     = \n| discharge1_avg     = {{convert|212|m3/s|cuft/s|abbr=on}}\n| discharge1_max     = \n<!---------------------- BASIN FEATURES -->\n| source1            = {{Coord|34.272303|N|75.529832|E|display=inline}}\n| source1_location   = [[Machoi Glacier]] near [[Zojila]]\n| source1_coordinates= \n| source1_elevation  = {{convert|4400|m|abbr=on}}\n| mouth              = {{Coord|34.5946|N|76.1202|E|display=inline,title}}\n| mouth_location     = [[Suru River (Indus)|Suru River]] at Kharul [[Kargil district|Kargil]]\n| mouth_coordinates  = \n| mouth_elevation    = {{convert|3618|m|abbr=on}}\n| progression        = \n| river_system       = \n| basin_size         = \n| tributaries_left   = \n| tributaries_right  = \n| custom_label       = \n| custom_data        = \n| extra              = \n}}\n\nThe '''Dras River''', also spelt '''Drass River''' , is a [[river]] in the [[Kargil district]] in the [[India]]n union territory of [[Ladakh]].\n\n== Course ==\nThe Dras River is {{convert|86|km|abbr=on}} long and flows entirely in the Dras Valley. Its [[river source|source]] lies in the [[Machoi Glacier]] near [[Zojila Pass]], the gateway to [[Ladakh]], {{convert|26|km|abbr=on}} east of [[Sonamarg]] and {{convert|120|km|abbr=on}} east of [[Srinagar]], the capital of Jammu and Kashmir.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gaffarakashmir.com/kargil.html|title=Kargil the Suru valley|publisher=gaffarkashmir.com|accessdate=2012-08-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190419140828/http://gaffarakashmir.com/kargil.html|archive-date=19 April 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Dras valley\">{{cite book | author=Omacanda H\u0101\u1e47\u1e0d\u0101 | title=Buddhist Western Himalaya: A politico-religious history |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R4VuovXa5YUC&pg=PA67&dq=dras+river&output=html_text&cd=9 | accessdate=27 August 2012 | year=2001 | publisher=Indus Publishing, 2001 | isbn=9788173871245 | page=-67}}</ref> The Machoi Glacier is also the source of the [[Sind River]], which flows through the neighbouring [[Kashmir Valley]] in the opposite direction to the Dras River.<ref name=\"Dras River\"/> The Dras River flows northeast, fed by many glacial streams. [[NH 1D]], a national highway connecting Srinagar with Ladakh ([[Kargil district|Kargil]] and [[Leh district|Leh]]), runs parallel to the river. The river forms the Dras Valley at [[Dras]],<ref name=\"Dras valley\"/> where it is joined by two tributaries, the Mashko Nala and Gamru Nala, which originate in the glaciers of Mashko Valley.<ref name=\"Dras River\">{{cite book | author=Harish Kapadia | title=Across Peaks & Passes in Ladakh, Zanskar & East Karakoram |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pl5qHu_K45kC&pg=PA226&dq=dras+river&output=html_text&cd=4 | accessdate=27 August 2012 | year=1999 | publisher=Indus Publishing, 1999 | isbn=9788173871009 | page=-226}}</ref> In the Dras Valley, the road connecting Dras and [[Gurais]] runs parallel to the river.\n\n[[File:Singomeetsdras.JPG|thumb|left|The confluence of Dras (left) and [[Shingo River]]s]]\nThe [[Shingo River]] joins the Dras River at Kharbu, and doubles the flow of the river. The Shingo River originates in the Chota Deosai Plains north of Minimarg ([[Astore District]], [[Gilgit-Baltistan]]) and flows east.<ref name=\"Kapadia1999\">{{citation |last=Kapadia |first=Harish |title=Across Peaks & Passes in Ladakh, Zanskar & East Karakoram |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pl5qHu_K45kC&pg=PA226 |year=1999 |publisher=Indus Publishing |isbn=978-81-7387-100-9 |pages=226\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Dras valley\"/>\n\nThe combined Dras and Shingo rivers join the [[Suru River (Indus)|Suru River]] at Kharul, {{convert|7|km|abbr=on}} north of the town of [[Kargil town|Kargil]].<ref name=\"Dras valley\"/> The Suru River is a left tributary of the [[Indus River]].<ref name=\"suru indus\">{{cite book | author=S. S. Negi | title=Cold Deserts of India |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=54RgJ6FgMl0C&pg=PA13&dq=suru+river+tributary+of+indus+river&output=html_text&cd=3 | accessdate=27 August 2012 | year=2002 | publisher=Indus Publishing, 2002 | isbn=9788173871276 | page=-13}}</ref> It originates from the Panzella glacier near [[Pensi La]], flows northwards and merges with the [[Indus River]] at Nurla in Pakistan-administered [[Gilgit-Baltistan]], {{convert|5|km|abbr=on}} north of its confluence with the Dras River. It enters the Pakistani-Administered Kashmir at Post 43 of India or Post 44 of Pakistan.<ref name=\"zanskar range\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ladakh.com/ladakh-info/rivers|title=Rivers of Ladakh|publisher=ladakh.com|accessdate=2012-08-29|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120902233945/http://www.ladakh.com/ladakh-info/rivers|archivedate=2012-09-02}}</ref>\n\n== Habitation ==\nThe Dras River flows through the towns of [[Matayan]], Kharbu and Kakshar. The largest settlement on its banks is [[Dras]], which is the second-coldest inhabited place in the world after [[Siberia]].<ref name=\"Drass valley\">{{cite book | author=M.S. Kohli | title=Mountains of India: Tourism, Adventure, Pilgrimage |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GIs4zv17HHwC&pg=PA124&dq=drass+coldest+place&output=html_text&cd=10 | accessdate=29 August 2012 | year=2004 | publisher=Indus Publishing, 2004 | isbn=9788173871351 | page=-124}}</ref> The water flow of the river increases during the late summer, due to the heavy melting of glaciers.<ref name=\"Dras River water flow\">{{cite book | author=Sharad Singh Negi | title=Himalayan Rivers, Lakes, and Glaciers Informative books on the himalayas-forestry-environment |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5YtUShKY8zcC&pg=PA61&dq=dras+river&output=html_text&cd=5 | accessdate=27 August 2012 | year=1991 | publisher=Indus Publishing, 1991 | isbn=9788185182612 | page=-61}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Baily Bridge]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book | author=William Moorcroft|authorlink = William Moorcroft (explorer)|author2= George Trebeck|authorlink2 = George Trebeck|author3= Horace Hayman Wilson|authorlink3= Horace Hayman Wilson | title=Travels in the Himalayan Provinces of Hindustan and the Panjab; in Ladakh and Kashmir; in Peshawar, Kabul, Kunduz, and Bokhara ...: From 1819 to 1825, Volume 2 |url=https://archive.org/details/travelsinhimala00trebgoog | quote=Shingo river.| accessdate=27 August 2012 | year=1841 | publisher=J. Murray, 1841 | isbn= | page=-261\u2013265}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Dras River}}\n* [https://www.openstreetmap.org/relation/1159554 Suru River basin on OpenStreetMap], including the Dras River\n\n{{Ladakh}}\n{{Hydrography of Ladakh}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers of Ladakh]]\n[[Category:Geography of Ladakh]]\n[[Category:Indus basin]]\n[[Category:Rivers of India]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox river\n| name               = Dras River\n| name_native        = \n| name_native_lang   = \n| name_other         = \n| name_etymology     = \n<!---------------------- IMAGE & MAP -->\n| image              = Drasvalley.JPG\n| image_size         = 290 px\n| image_caption      = Dras River\n| map                = \n| map_size           = \n| map_caption        = \n| pushpin_map        = India Ladakh\n| pushpin_map_size   = \n| pushpin_map_caption= The confluence of the Dras River with the Suru River\n<!---------------------- LOCATION -->\n| subdivision_type1  = Country\n| subdivision_name1  = [[India]]\n| subdivision_type2  = Union territory\n| subdivision_name2  = [[Ladakh]]\n| subdivision_type3  = District\n| subdivision_name3  = [[Kargil district|Kargil]]\n<!---------------------- PHYSICAL CHARACTERISTICS -->\n| length             = {{convert|86|km|mi|abbr=on}} \n| width_min          = \n| width_avg          = \n| width_max          = \n| depth_min          = \n| depth_avg          = \n| depth_max          = \n| discharge1_location= \n| discharge1_min     = \n| discharge1_avg     = {{convert|212|m3/s|cuft/s|abbr=on}}\n| discharge1_max     = \n<!---------------------- BASIN FEATURES -->\n| source1            = {{Coord|34.272303|N|75.529832|E|display=inline}}\n| source1_location   = [[Machoi Glacier]] near [[Zojila]]\n| source1_coordinates= \n| source1_elevation  = {{convert|4400|m|abbr=on}}\n| mouth              = {{Coord|34.5946|N|76.1202|E|display=inline,title}}\n| mouth_location     = [[Suru River (Indus)|Suru River]] at Kharul [[Kargil district|Kargil]]\n| mouth_coordinates  = \n| mouth_elevation    = {{convert|3618|m|abbr=on}}\n| progression        = \n| river_system       = \n| basin_size         = \n| tributaries_left   = \n| tributaries_right  = \n| custom_label       = \n| custom_data        = \n| extra              = \n}}\n\nThe '''Dras River''', also spelt '''Drass River''' , is a [[river]] in the [[Kargil district]] in the [[India]]n union territory of [[Ladakh]].\n\n== Course ==\nThe Dras River is {{convert|86|km|abbr=on}} long and flows entirely in the Dras Valley. Its [[river source|source]] lies in the [[Machoi Glacier]] near [[Zojila Pass]], the gateway to [[Ladakh]], {{convert|26|km|abbr=on}} east of [[Sonamarg]] and {{convert|120|km|abbr=on}} east of [[Srinagar]], the capital of Jammu and Kashmir.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gaffarakashmir.com/kargil.html|title=Kargil the Suru valley|publisher=gaffarkashmir.com|accessdate=2012-08-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190419140828/http://gaffarakashmir.com/kargil.html|archive-date=19 April 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Dras valley\">{{cite book | author=Omacanda H\u0101\u1e47\u1e0d\u0101 | title=Buddhist Western Himalaya: A politico-religious history |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R4VuovXa5YUC&pg=PA67&dq=dras+river&output=html_text&cd=9 | accessdate=27 August 2012 | year=2001 | publisher=Indus Publishing, 2001 | isbn=9788173871245 | page=-67}}</ref> The Machoi Glacier is also the source of the [[Sind River]], which flows through the neighbouring [[Kashmir Valley]] in the opposite direction to the Dras River.<ref name=\"Dras River\"/> The Dras River flows northeast, fed by many glacial streams. [[NH 1D]], a national highway connecting Srinagar with Ladakh ([[Kargil district|Kargil]] and [[Leh district|Leh]]), runs parallel to the river. The river forms the Dras Valley at [[Dras]],<ref name=\"Dras valley\"/> where it is joined by two tributaries, the Mashko Nala and Gamru Nala, which originate in the glaciers of Mashko Valley.<ref name=\"Dras River\">{{cite book | author=Harish Kapadia | title=Across Peaks & Passes in Ladakh, Zanskar & East Karakoram |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pl5qHu_K45kC&pg=PA226&dq=dras+river&output=html_text&cd=4 | accessdate=27 August 2012 | year=1999 | publisher=Indus Publishing, 1999 | isbn=9788173871009 | page=-226}}</ref> In the Dras Valley, the road connecting Dras and [[Gurais]] runs parallel to the river.\n\n[[File:Singomeetsdras.JPG|thumb|left|The confluence of Dras (left) and [[Shingo River]]s]]\nThe [[Shingo River]] joins the Dras River at Kharbu, and doubles the flow of the river. The Shingo River originates in the Chota Deosai Plains north of Minimarg ([[Astore District]], [[Gilgit-Baltistan]]) and flows east.<ref name=\"Kapadia1999\">{{citation |last=Kapadia |first=Harish |title=Across Peaks & Passes in Ladakh, Zanskar & East Karakoram |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pl5qHu_K45kC&pg=PA226 |year=1999 |publisher=Indus Publishing |isbn=978-81-7387-100-9 |pages=226\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Dras valley\"/>\n\nThe combined Dras and Shingo rivers join the [[Suru River (Indus)|Suru River]] at Kharul, {{convert|7|km|abbr=on}} north of the town of [[Kargil town|Kargil]].<ref name=\"Dras valley\"/> The Suru River is a left tributary of the [[Indus River]].<ref name=\"suru indus\">{{cite book | author=S. S. Negi | title=Cold Deserts of India |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=54RgJ6FgMl0C&pg=PA13&dq=suru+river+tributary+of+indus+river&output=html_text&cd=3 | accessdate=27 August 2012 | year=2002 | publisher=Indus Publishing, 2002 | isbn=9788173871276 | page=-13}}</ref> It originates from the Panzella glacier near [[Pensi La]], flows northwards and merges with the [[Indus River]] at Nurla in Pakistan-administered [[Gilgit-Baltistan]], {{convert|5|km|abbr=on}} north of its confluence with the Dras River. It enters the Pakistani-Administered Kashmir at Post 43 of India or Post 44 of Pakistan.<ref name=\"zanskar range\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ladakh.com/ladakh-info/rivers|title=Rivers of Ladakh|publisher=ladakh.com|accessdate=2012-08-29|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120902233945/http://www.ladakh.com/ladakh-info/rivers|archivedate=2012-09-02}}</ref>\n\n== Habitation ==\nThe Dras River flows through the towns of [[Matayan]], Kharbu and Kakshar. The largest settlement on its banks is [[Dras]], which is the second-coldest inhabited place in the world after [[Siberia]].<ref name=\"Drass valley\">{{cite book | author=M.S. Kohli | title=Mountains of India: Tourism, Adventure, Pilgrimage |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GIs4zv17HHwC&pg=PA124&dq=drass+coldest+place&output=html_text&cd=10 | accessdate=29 August 2012 | year=2004 | publisher=Indus Publishing, 2004 | isbn=9788173871351 | page=-124}}</ref> The water flow of the river increases during the late summer, due to the heavy melting of glaciers.<ref name=\"Dras River water flow\">{{cite book | author=Sharad Singh Negi | title=Himalayan Rivers, Lakes, and Glaciers Informative books on the himalayas-forestry-environment |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5YtUShKY8zcC&pg=PA61&dq=dras+river&output=html_text&cd=5 | accessdate=27 August 2012 | year=1991 | publisher=Indus Publishing, 1991 | isbn=9788185182612 | page=-61}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Baily Bridge]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book | author=William Moorcroft|authorlink = William Moorcroft (explorer)|author2= George Trebeck|authorlink2 = George Trebeck|author3= Horace Hayman Wilson|authorlink3= Horace Hayman Wilson | title=Travels in the Himalayan Provinces of Hindustan and the Panjab; in Ladakh and Kashmir; in Peshawar, Kabul, Kunduz, and Bokhara ...: From 1819 to 1825, Volume 2 |url=https://archive.org/details/travelsinhimala00trebgoog | quote=Shingo river.| accessdate=27 August 2012 | year=1841 | publisher=J. Murray, 1841 | isbn= | page=-261\u2013265}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Dras River}}\n* [https://www.openstreetmap.org/relation/1159554 Suru River basin on OpenStreetMap], including the Dras River\n\n{{Ladakh}}\n{{Hydrography of Jammu and Kashmir}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers of Ladakh]]\n[[Category:Geography of Ladakh]]\n[[Category:Indus basin]]\n[[Category:Rivers of India]]\n", "name_user": "FlyJet777", "label": "safe", "